# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rewindpix
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] An **autofocus** (**AF**) optical system uses a sensor, a control system and a motor to focus on an automatically or manually selected point or area.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] An electronic rangefinder has a display instead of the motor; the adjustment of the optical system has to be done manually until indication.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Autofocus methods are distinguished as active, passive or hybrid types.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Autofocus systems rely on one or more sensors to determine correct focus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Some AF systems rely on a single sensor, while others use an array of sensors.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Most modern SLR cameras use through-the-lens optical sensors, with a separate sensor array providing light metering, although the latter can be programmed to prioritize its metering to the same area as one or more of the AF sensors.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Through-the-lens optical autofocusing is usually speedier and more precise than manual focus with an ordinary viewfinder, although more precise manual focus can be achieved with special accessories such as focusing magnifiers.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Autofocus accuracy within 1/3 of the depth of field (DOF) at the widest aperture of the lens is common in professional AF SLR cameras.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Most multi-sensor AF cameras allow manual selection of the active sensor, and many offer automatic selection of the sensor using algorithms which attempt to discern the location of the subject.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Some AF cameras are able to detect whether the subject is moving towards or away from the camera, including speed and acceleration, and keep focus — a function used mainly in sports and other action photography.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Canon cameras call this AI servo; Nikon cameras call it "continuous focus".
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The data collected from AF sensors is used to control an electromechanical system that adjusts the focus of the optical system.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] A variation of autofocus is an *electronic rangefinder*, in which focus data are provided to the operator, but adjustment of the optical system is still performed manually.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The speed of the AF system is highly dependent on the widest aperture offered by the lens at the current focal length.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] F-stops of around f/2 to f/2.8 are generally considered best for focusing speed and accuracy.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Faster lenses than this (e.g.: f/1.4 or f/1.8) typically have very low depth of field, meaning that it takes longer to achieve correct focus, despite the increased amount of light.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Most consumer camera systems will only autofocus reliably with lenses that have a widest aperture of at least f/5.6, whilst professional models can often cope with a widest aperture of f/8, which is particularly useful for lenses used in conjunction with teleconverters.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Between 1960 and 1973, Leitz (Leica) patented an array of autofocus and corresponding sensor technologies.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] In 1976, Leica had presented a camera based on their previous development at Photokina, named Correfot, and in 1978 they displayed an SLR camera with fully operational autofocus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The first mass-produced autofocus camera was the Konica C35 AF, a simple point and shoot model released in 1977.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The Polaroid SX-70 Sonar OneStep was the first autofocus single-lens reflex camera, released in 1978.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The Pentax ME-F, which used focus sensors in the camera body coupled with a motorized lens, became the first autofocus 35 mm SLR in 1981.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] In 1983 Nikon released the F3AF, their first autofocus camera, which was based on a similar concept to the ME-F.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Canon decided to discontinue their FD mount and switched to the completely electronic EF mount with motorised lenses in 1987.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Pentax was the first to introduce focusing distance measurement for SLR cameras with the FA and FA* series lenses from 1991.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Their first KAF-mount Pentax lenses with AF had been introduced in 1989.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] In 1992, Nikon changed back to lens integrated motors with their AF-I and AF-S range of lenses; today their entry-level DSLRs do not have a focus motor in the body due to the availability of motors in all new developed AF-Lenses.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Active AF systems measure distance to the subject independently of the optical system, and subsequently adjust the optical system for correct focus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] There are various ways to measure distance, including ultrasonic sound waves and infrared light.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] In the first case, sound waves are emitted from the camera, and by measuring the delay in their reflection, distance to the subject is calculated.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Polaroid cameras including the Spectra and SX-70 were known for successfully applying this system.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] In the latter case, infrared light is usually used to triangulate the distance to the subject.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Compact cameras including the Nikon 35TiQD and 28TiQD, the Canon AF35M, and the Contax T2 and T3, as well as early video cameras, used this system.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] A newer approach included in some consumer electronic devices, like mobile phones, is based on the time-of-flight principle, which involves shining a laser or LED light to the subject and calculating the distance based on the time it takes for the light to travel to the subject and back.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] This technique is sometimes called *laser autofocus*, and is present in many mobile phone models from several vendors.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] It is also present in industrial and medical devices.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] An exception to the two-step approach is the mechanical autofocus provided in some enlargers, which adjust the lens directly.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Passive AF systems determine correct focus by performing passive analysis of the image that is entering the optical system.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] They generally do not direct any energy, such as ultrasonic sound or infrared light waves, toward the subject.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] (However, an autofocus assist beam of usually infrared light is required when there is not enough light to take passive measurements.) Passive autofocusing can be achieved by phase detection or contrast measurement.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Phase detection (PD) is achieved by dividing the incoming light into pairs of images and comparing them.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Through-the-lens **secondary image registration** (**TTL SIR**) passive phase detection is often used in film and digital SLR cameras.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The system uses a beam splitter (implemented as a small semi-transparent area of the main reflex mirror, coupled with a small secondary mirror) to direct light to an AF sensor at the bottom of the camera.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Two micro-lenses capture the light rays coming from the opposite sides of the lens and divert it to the AF sensor, creating a simple rangefinder with a base within the lens's diameter.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The two images are then analysed for similar light intensity patterns (peaks and valleys) and the separation error is calculated in order to find whether the object is in front focus or back focus position.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] This gives the direction and an estimate of the required amount of focus-ring movement.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] PD AF in a continuously focusing mode (e.g.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] "AI Servo" for Canon, "AF-C" for Nikon, Pentax and Sony) is a closed-loop control process.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] "One-Shot" for Canon, "AF-S" for Nikon and Sony) is widely believed to be a "one measurement, one movement" open-loop control process, but focus is confirmed only when the AF sensor sees an in-focus subject.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The only apparent differences between the two modes are that a focus-locking mode halts on focus confirmation, and a continuously focusing mode has predictive elements to work with moving targets, which suggests they are the same closed-loop process.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Cross-type focus points have a pair of sensors oriented at 90° to one another, although one sensor typically requires a larger aperture to operate than the other.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Some modern sensors (for example one in Librem 5) include about 2% phase detection pixels on the chip.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] With suitable software support, that enables phase detection auto focus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Contrast-detection autofocus is achieved by measuring contrast (vision) within a sensor field through the lens.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The intensity difference between adjacent pixels of the sensor naturally increases with correct image focus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The optical system can thereby be adjusted until the maximal contrast is detected.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] In this method, AF does not involve actual distance measurement at all.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] This creates significant challenges when tracking moving subjects, since a loss of contrast gives no indication of the direction of motion towards or away from the camera.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Contrast-detect autofocus is a common method in digital cameras that lack shutters and reflex mirrors.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Most DSLRs use this method (or a hybrid of both contrast and phase-detection autofocus) when focusing in their live-view modes.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] A notable exception is Canon digital cameras with Dual Pixel CMOS AF.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras typically used contrast-measurement autofocus, although phase detection has become the norm on most mirrorless cameras giving them significantly better AF tracking performance compared to contrast detection.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Contrast detection places different constraints on lens design when compared with phase detection.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] While phase detection requires the lens to move its focus point quickly and directly to a new position, contrast-detection autofocus instead employs lenses that can quickly sweep through the focal range, stopping precisely at the point where maximal contrast is detected.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] This means that lenses designed for phase detection often perform poorly on camera bodies that use contrast detection.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The assist light (also known as AF illuminator) "activates" passive autofocus systems in low-light and low-contrast situations in some cameras.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The lamp projects visible or IR light onto the subject, which the camera's autofocus system uses to achieve focus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Many cameras and nearly all camera phones lack a dedicated autofocus assist lamp.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Instead, they use their built-in flash, illuminating the subject with bursts of light.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] This aids the autofocus system in the same fashion as a dedicated assist light, but has the disadvantage of startling or annoying people.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Another disadvantage is that if the camera uses flash focus assist and is set to an operation mode that overrides the flash, it may also disable the focus assist.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Thus, autofocus may fail to acquire the subject.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Similar stroboscopic flashing is sometimes used to reduce the red-eye effect, but this is only intended to constrict the subject's eye pupils before the shot.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Some external flash guns have integrated autofocus assist lamps that replace the stroboscopic on-camera flash.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Many of them are red and less obtrusive.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Similar to a laser rangefinder, autofocus systems can project a patterned laser toward the subject.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The laser method is used by Sony, both in their Cyber-shot cameras since 2003, under the name *Hologram AF Laser*, and in some of their smartphones since and including the Xperia XZ.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The double effort is typically used to mutually compensate for the intrinsical weaknesses of the various methods in order to increase the overall reliability and accuracy or to speed up AF function.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] A rare example of an early hybrid system is the combination of an active IR or ultrasonic auto-focus system with a passive phase-detection system.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] An IR or ultrasonic system based on reflection will work regardless of the light conditions, but can be easily fooled by obstacles like window glasses, and the accuracy is typically restricted to a rather limited number of steps.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Phase-detection autofocus "sees" through window glasses without problems and is much more accurate, but it does not work in low-light conditions or on surfaces without contrasts or with repeating patterns.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] A very common example of combined usage is the phase-detection auto-focus system used in single-lens reflex cameras since the 1985s.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The passive phase-detection auto-focus needs some contrast to work with, making it difficult to use in low-light scenarios or on even surfaces.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] An AF illuminator will illuminate the scene and project contrast patterns onto even surfaces, so that phase-detection auto-focus can work under these conditions as well.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] A newer form of a hybrid system is the combination of passive phase-detection auto-focus and passive contrast auto-focus, sometimes assisted by active methods, as both methods need some visible contrast to work with.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Under their operational conditions, phase-detection auto-focusing is very fast, since the measurement method provides both information, the amount of offset and the direction, so that the focusing motor can move the lens right into (or close to) focus without additional measurements.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Additional measurements on the fly, however, can improve accuracy or help keep track of moving objects.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] However, the accuracy of phase-detection auto-focus depends on its effective measurement basis.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] If the measurement basis is large, measurements are very accurate, but can only work with lenses with a large geometrical aperture (e.g.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Even with high contrasty objects, phase-detection AF cannot work at all with lenses slower than its effective measurement basis.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] In order to work with most lenses, the effective measurement basis is typically set to between 1:5.6 and 1:6.7, so that AF continues to work with slow lenses (at least for as long as they are not stopped down).
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] This, however, reduces the intrinsical accuracy of the autofocus system, even if fast lenses are used.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Since the effective measurement basis is an optical property of the actual implementation, it cannot be changed easily.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Very few cameras provide multi-PD-AF systems with several switchable measurement bases depending on the lens used in order to allow normal auto-focusing with most lenses, and more accurate focusing with fast lenses.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Contrast AF does not have this inherent design limitation on accuracy as it only needs a minimal object contrast to work with.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Once this is available, it can work with high accuracy regardless of the speed of a lens; in fact, for as long as this condition is met, it can even work with the lens stopped down.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Also, since contrast AF continues to work in stopped-down mode rather than only in open-aperture mode, it is immune to aperture-based focus shift errors phase-detection AF systems suffer since they cannot work in stopped-down mode.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Thereby, contrast AF makes arbitrary fine-focus adjustments by the user unnecessary.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Also, contrast AF is immune to focusing errors due to surfaces with repeating patterns and they can work over the whole frame, not just near the center of the frame, as phase-detection AF does.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The down-side, however, is that contrast AF is a closed-loop iterative process of shifting the focus back and forth in rapid succession.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Compared to phase-detection AF, contrast AF is slow, since the speed of the focus iteration process is mechanically limited and this measurement method does not provide any directional information.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Combining both measurement methods, the phase-detection AF can assist a contrast AF system to be fast and accurate at the same time, to compensate aperture-based focus-shift errors, and to continue to work with lenses stopped down, as, for example, in stopped-down measuring or video mode.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Recent developments towards mirrorless cameras seek to integrate the phase-detection AF sensors into the image sensor itself.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] In July, 2010, Fujifilm announced a compact camera, the F300EXR, which included a hybrid autofocus system consisting of both phase-detection and contrast-based elements.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The sensors implementing the phase-detection AF in this camera are integrated into the camera's Super CCD EXR.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Currently it is used by Fujifilm FinePix Series, Fujifilm X100S, Ricoh, Nikon 1 series, Canon EOS 650D/Rebel T4i and Samsung NX300.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Active systems will typically not focus through windows, since sound waves and infrared light are reflected by the glass.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] With passive systems this will generally not be a problem, unless the window is stained.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Accuracy of active autofocus systems is often considerably less than that of passive systems.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Active systems may also fail to focus a subject that is very close to the camera (e.g., macro photography).
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Passive systems may not find focus when the contrast is low, notably on large single-colored surfaces (walls, blue sky, etc.) or in low-light conditions.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Passive systems are dependent on a certain degree of illumination to the subject (whether natural or otherwise), while active systems may focus correctly even in total darkness when necessary.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Some cameras and external flash units have a special low-level illumination mode (usually orange/red light) which can be activated during auto-focus operation to allow the camera to focus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] This is done by using AF to *detect* but not *set* focus – using manual focus to set focus (or switching to manual after focus has been set) but then using *focus priority* to detect focus and only release the shutter when an object is in focus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The first SLR to implement trap focusing was the Yashica 230 AF.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Trap focus is also possible on some Pentax (e.g.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] K-x and K-5), Nikon, and Canon EOS cameras.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The EOS 1D can do it using software on an attached computer, whereas cameras like the EOS 40D and 7D have a custom function (III-1 and III-4 respectively) which can stop the camera trying to focus after it fails.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] On EOS cameras without genuine trap focus, a hack called "almost trap focus" can be used, which achieves some of the effects of trap focus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] By using the custom firmware Magic Lantern, some Canon DSLRs can perform trap focus.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] AI Servo is an autofocus mode found on Canon SLR cameras, and in other brands such as Nikon, Sony, and Pentax, under the name "continuous focus" (AF-C).
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Also referred to as *focus tracking*, it is used to track a subject as it moves around the frame, or toward and away from the camera.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] When in use, the lens will constantly maintain its focus on the subject, hence it is commonly used for sports and action photography.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] AI refers to artificial intelligence: algorithms that constantly predict where a subject is about to be based on its speed and acceleration data from the autofocus sensor.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Modern autofocus is done through one of two mechanisms; either a motor in the camera body and gears in the lens ("screw drive") or through electronic transmission of the drive instruction through contacts in the mount plate to a motor in the lens.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Lens-based motors can be of a number of different types, but are often ultrasonic motors or stepper motors.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Magnets are often used in electromagnetic motors, such as Voice coil motors (VCMs) and Stepper motor, which move the lens elements to achieve precise focusing.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] The magnetic field interacts with coils to produce motion for adjusting the lens position quickly and accurately based on focus requirements.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Magnets are ideal for this purpose because they enable smooth and rapid adjustments without direct physical contact, enhancing durability and response time.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Some camera bodies, including all Canon EOS bodies and the more budget-oriented among Nikon's DX models, do not include an autofocus motor and therefore cannot autofocus with lenses that lack an inbuilt motor.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Some lenses, such as Pentax' DA* designated models, although normally using an inbuilt motor, can fall back to screwdrive operation when the camera body does not support the necessary contact pins.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] In photography, **manual focus override**, also known as **full-time manual focus**, allows manual intervention in the autofocus acquisition process simply by turning the focus ring on a photographic lens.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] There are a number of technologies used to implement this feature.
[src:rewindpix/autofocus] Pentax uses the trademark *Quick Shift* to refer to its implementations of manual focus override.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Players advance the ball by bouncing it while walking or running (dribbling) or by passing it to a teammate, both of which require considerable skill.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] On offense, players may use a variety of shots – the layup, the jump shot, or a dunk.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] On defense, they may steal the ball from a dribbler, intercept passes, or block shots.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Either offense, or defense may collect a rebound, which is a missed shot that bounces from rim or backboard.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] It is a violation to lift or drag one's pivot foot without dribbling the ball, to carry it, or to hold the ball with both hands then resume dribbling.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The five players on each side fall into five playing positions.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The tallest player is typically the center, the second-tallest and strongest is the power forward.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The small forward is a shorter, but very agile player.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Lastly, the shortest players or the best ball handlers are the shooting guard and the point guard.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] These players implement the coach's game plan by managing the execution of offensive and defensive plays (player positioning).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Informally, players may play three-on-three, two-on-two, and one-on-one.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Invented in 1891 by Canadian-American gym teacher James Naismith in Springfield, Massachusetts, in the United States, basketball has evolved to become one of the world's most popular and widely viewed sports.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The National Basketball Association (NBA) is the most significant professional basketball league in the world in terms of popularity, salaries, talent, and level of competition (drawing most of its talent from U.S. college basketball).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Outside North America, the top clubs from national leagues qualify to continental championships such as the EuroLeague and the Basketball Champions League Americas.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The FIBA Basketball World Cup and Men's Olympic Basketball Tournament are the major international events of the sport and attract top national teams from around the world.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Each continent hosts regional competitions for national teams, like EuroBasket and FIBA AmeriCup.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup and women's Olympic basketball tournament feature top national teams from continental championships.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The main North American league is the WNBA (NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Championship is also popular), whereas the strongest European clubs participate in the EuroLeague Women.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In December 1891, James Naismith, a Canadian-American professor of physical education and instructor at the International Young Men's Christian Association Training School (now Springfield College) in Springfield, Massachusetts, was trying to keep his gym class active on a rainy day.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] He sought a vigorous indoor game to keep his students occupied and at proper levels of fitness during the long New England winters.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] After rejecting other ideas as either too rough or poorly suited to walled-in gymnasiums, he invented a new game in which players would pass a ball to teammates and try to score points by tossing the ball into a basket mounted on a wall.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Naismith wrote the basic rules and nailed a peach basket onto an elevated track.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Naismith initially set up the peach basket with its bottom intact, which meant that the ball had to be retrieved manually after each "basket" or point scored.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] This quickly proved tedious, so Naismith removed the bottom of the basket to allow the balls to be poked out with a long dowel after each scored basket.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Shortly after, Senda Berenson, instructor of physical culture at the nearby Smith College, went to Naismith to learn more about the game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Fascinated by the new sport and the values it could teach, she started to organize games with her pupils, following adjusted rules.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first official women's interinstitutional game was played barely 11 months later, between the University of California and Miss Head's School.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1899, a committee was established at the Conference of Physical Training in Springfield to draw up general rules for women's basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Thus, the sport quickly spread throughout America's schools, colleges and universities with uniform rules for both sexes.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Basketball was originally played with a soccer ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] These round balls from "association football" were made, at the time, with a set of laces to close off the hole needed for inserting the inflatable bladder after the other sewn-together segments of the ball's cover had been flipped outside-in.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] These laces could cause bounce passes and dribbling to be unpredictable.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Eventually a lace-free ball construction method was invented, and this change to the game was endorsed by Naismith (whereas in American football, the lace construction proved to be advantageous for gripping and remains to this day).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first balls made specifically for basketball were brown, and it was only in the late 1950s that Tony Hinkle, searching for a ball that would be more visible to players and spectators alike, introduced the orange ball that is now in common use.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Dribbling was not part of the original game except for the "bounce pass" to teammates.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Passing the ball was the primary means of ball movement.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Dribbling was eventually introduced but limited by the asymmetric shape of early balls.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Dribbling was common by 1896, with a rule against the double dribble by 1898.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The peach baskets were used until 1906 when they were finally replaced by metal hoops with backboards.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A further change was soon made, so the ball merely passed through.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Whenever a person got the ball in the basket, their team would gain a point.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Whichever team got the most points won the game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The baskets were originally nailed to the mezzanine balcony of the playing court, but this proved impractical when spectators in the balcony began to interfere with shots.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The backboard was introduced to prevent this interference; it had the additional effect of allowing rebound shots.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Naismith's handwritten diaries, discovered by his granddaughter in early 2006, indicate that he was nervous about the new game he had invented, which incorporated rules from a children's game called duck on a rock, as many had failed before it.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Frank Mahan, one of the players from the original first game, approached Naismith after the Christmas break, in early 1892, asking him what he intended to call his new game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Naismith replied that he had not thought of it because he had been focused on just getting the game started.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Mahan suggested that it be called "Naismith ball", at which he laughed, saying that a name like that would kill any game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Mahan then said, "Why not call it basketball?" Naismith replied, "We have a basket and a ball, and it seems to me that would be a good name for it." The first official game was played in the YMCA gymnasium in Albany, New York, on January 20, 1892, with nine players.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The game ended at 1–0; the shot was made from 25 feet (7.6 m), on a court just half the size of a present-day Streetball or National Basketball Association (NBA) court.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] At the time, soccer was being played with 10 to a team (which was increased to 11).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] When winter weather got too icy to play soccer, teams were taken indoors, and it was convenient to have them split in half and play basketball with five on each side.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] By 1897–98, teams of five became standard.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Basketball's early adherents were dispatched to YMCAs throughout the United States, and it quickly spread through the United States and Canada.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] By 1895, it was well established at several women's high schools.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] While YMCA was responsible for initially developing and spreading the game, within a decade it discouraged the new sport, as rough play and rowdy crowds began to detract from YMCA's primary mission.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] However, other amateur sports clubs, colleges, and professional clubs quickly filled the void.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In the years before World War I, the Amateur Athletic Union and the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States (forerunner of the NCAA) vied for control over the rules for the game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first pro league, the National Basketball League, was formed in 1898 to protect players from exploitation and to promote a less rough game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] James Naismith was instrumental in establishing college basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Beamis fielded the first college basketball team just a year after the Springfield YMCA game at the suburban Pittsburgh Geneva College.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Naismith himself later coached at the University of Kansas for six years, before handing the reins to renowned coach Forrest "Phog" Allen.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Naismith's disciple Amos Alonzo Stagg brought basketball to the University of Chicago, while Adolph Rupp, a student of Naismith's at Kansas, enjoyed great success as coach at the University of Kentucky.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] On February 9, 1895, the first intercollegiate 5-on-5 game was played at Hamline University between Hamline and the School of Agriculture, which was affiliated with the University of Minnesota.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The School of Agriculture won in a 9–3 game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1901, colleges, including the University of Chicago, Columbia University, Cornell University, Dartmouth College, the University of Minnesota, the U.S.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Naval Academy, the University of Colorado and Yale University began sponsoring men's games.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1905, frequent injuries on the football field prompted President Theodore Roosevelt to suggest that colleges form a governing body, resulting in the creation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States (IAAUS).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1910, that body changed its name to the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first Canadian interuniversity basketball game was played at YMCA in Kingston, Ontario on February 6, 1904, when McGill University – Naismith's alma mater – visited Queen's University.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] McGill won 9–7 in overtime; the score was 7–7 at the end of regulation play, and a ten-minute overtime period settled the outcome.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A good turnout of spectators watched the game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first men's national championship tournament, the National Association of Intercollegiate Basketball tournament, which still exists as the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) tournament, was organized in 1937.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first national championship for NCAA teams, the National Invitation Tournament (NIT) in New York, was organized in 1938; the NCAA national tournament began one year later.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] College basketball was rocked by gambling scandals from 1948 to 1951, when dozens of players from top teams were implicated in game-fixing and point shaving.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Partially spurred by an association with cheating, the NIT lost support to the NCAA tournament.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Before widespread school district consolidation, most American high schools were far smaller than their present-day counterparts.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] During the first decades of the 20th century, basketball quickly became the ideal interscholastic sport due to its modest equipment and personnel requirements.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In the days before widespread television coverage of professional and college sports, the popularity of high school basketball was unrivaled in many parts of America.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Perhaps the most legendary of high school teams was Indiana's Franklin Wonder Five, which took the nation by storm during the 1920s, dominating Indiana basketball and earning national recognition.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Today virtually every high school in the United States fields a basketball team in varsity competition.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Basketball's popularity remains high, both in rural areas where they carry the identification of the entire community, as well as at some larger schools known for their basketball teams where many players go on to participate at higher levels of competition after graduation.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In the 2016–17 season, 980,673 boys and girls represented their schools in interscholastic basketball competition, according to the National Federation of State High School Associations.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The states of Illinois, Indiana, and Kentucky are particularly well known for their residents' devotion to high school basketball, commonly called Hoosier Hysteria in Indiana; the critically acclaimed film *Hoosiers* shows high school basketball's depth of meaning to these communities.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] ⁣There is currently no tournament to determine a national high school champion.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The most serious effort was the National Interscholastic Basketball Tournament at the University of Chicago from 1917 to 1930.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The event was organized by Amos Alonzo Stagg and sent invitations to state champion teams.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The tournament started out as a mostly Midwest affair but grew.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Faced with opposition from the National Federation of State High School Associations and North Central Association of Colleges and Schools that bore a threat of the schools losing their accreditation the last tournament was in 1930.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The organizations said they were concerned that the tournament was being used to recruit professional players from the prep ranks.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The tournament did not invite minority schools or private/parochial schools.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The National Catholic Interscholastic Basketball Tournament ran from 1924 to 1941 at Loyola University.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The National Catholic Invitational Basketball Tournament from 1954 to 1978 played at a series of venues, including Catholic University, Georgetown and George Mason.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The National Interscholastic Basketball Tournament for Black High Schools was held from 1929 to 1942 at Hampton Institute.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The National Invitational Interscholastic Basketball Tournament was held from 1941 to 1967 starting out at Tuskegee Institute.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Following a pause during World War II it resumed at Tennessee State College in Nashville.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The basis for the champion dwindled after 1954 when *Brown v.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Board of Education* began an integration of schools.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The last tournaments were held at Alabama State College from 1964 to 1967.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] There were hundreds of men's professional basketball teams in towns and cities all over the United States, and little organization of the professional game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Players jumped from team to team and teams played in armories and smoky dance halls.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Barnstorming squads such as the Original Celtics and two all-African American teams, the New York Renaissance Five ("Rens") and the (still existing) Harlem Globetrotters played up to two hundred games a year on their national tours.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1946, the Basketball Association of America (BAA) was formed.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first game was played in Toronto, Ontario, Canada between the Toronto Huskies and New York Knickerbockers on November 1, 1946.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Three seasons later, in 1949, the BAA merged with the National Basketball League (NBL) to form the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] By the 1950s, basketball had become a major college sport, thus paving the way for a growth of interest in professional basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1959, a basketball hall of fame was founded in Springfield, Massachusetts, site of the first game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Its rosters include the names of great players, coaches, referees and people who have contributed significantly to the development of the game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The hall of fame has people who have accomplished many goals in their career in basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] An upstart organization, the American Basketball Association, emerged in 1967 and briefly threatened the NBA's dominance until the ABA-NBA merger in 1976.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Today the NBA is the top professional basketball league in the world in terms of popularity, salaries, talent, and level of competition.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The NBA has featured many famous players, including; George "Big Man" Mikan, ball-handling wizard Bob Cousy, defensive pro Bill Russell and the charismatic center, Wilt Chamberlain.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] All-around stars include; Oscar Robertson and Jerry West, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Shaquille O'Neal, Hakeem Olajuwon, and Karl Malone.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Other star playmakers like John Stockton, Isiah Thomas and Steve Nash.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Notable crowd-pleasing forwards are Julius Erving and Charles Barkley.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The list include European stars; Dirk Nowitzki, Pau Gasol, Nikola Jokić, and Tony Parker; Latin American star Manu Ginobili, and modern pro-superstars like Allen Iverson, Kobe Bryant, Tim Duncan, LeBron James, Stephen Curry, Giannis Antetokounmpo, and many more.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The three players who many credit with ushering the professional game to its highest level of popularity during the 1980s and 1990s: Larry Bird, Earvin "Magic" Johnson, and Michael Jordan.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 2001, the NBA formed a developmental league, the National Basketball Development League (later known as the NBA D-League and then the NBA G League after a branding deal with Gatorade).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] As of the 2023–24 season, the G League has 31 teams.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] FIBA (International Basketball Federation) was formed in 1932 by eight founding nations: Argentina, Czechoslovakia, Greece, Italy, Latvia, Portugal, Romania, and Switzerland.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] At this time, the organization only oversaw amateur players.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Its acronym, derived from the French *Fédération Internationale de Basket-ball Amateur*, was thus "FIBA".
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Men's basketball was first included at the Berlin 1936 Summer Olympics, although a demonstration tournament was held in 1904.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The United States defeated Canada in the first final, played outdoors.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] This competition has usually been dominated by the United States, whose team has won all but three titles.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first of these came in a controversial final game in Munich in 1972 against the Soviet Union, in which the ending of the game was replayed three times until the Soviet Union finally came out on top.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1950, the first FIBA World Championship for men, now known as the FIBA Basketball World Cup, was held in Argentina.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Three years later, the first FIBA World Championship for women, now known as the FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup, was held in Chile.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Women's basketball was added to the Olympics in 1976, which were held in Montreal, Quebec, Canada with teams such as the Soviet Union, Brazil, and Australia rivaling the American squads.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1989, FIBA allowed professional NBA players to participate in the Olympics for the first time.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Prior to the 1992 Summer Olympics, only European and South American teams were allowed to field professionals in the Olympics.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The United States' dominance continued with the introduction of the original Dream Team.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In the 2004 Athens Olympics, the United States suffered its first Olympic loss while using professional players, falling to Puerto Rico (in a 19-point loss) and Lithuania in group games, and being eliminated in the semifinals by Argentina.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] It eventually won the bronze medal defeating Lithuania, finishing behind Argentina and Italy.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The Redeem Team, won gold at the 2008 Olympics, and the B-Team, won gold at the 2010 FIBA World Championship in Turkey despite featuring no players from the 2008 squad.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The United States continued its dominance as they won gold at the 2012 Olympics, 2014 FIBA World Cup, 2016 Olympics, 2020 Olympics, and 2024 Olympics.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Worldwide, basketball tournaments are held for boys and girls of all age levels.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The global popularity of the sport is reflected in the nationalities represented in the NBA.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Players from all six inhabited continents currently play in the NBA.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Top international players began coming into the NBA in the mid-1990s, including Croatians Dražen Petrović and Toni Kukoč, Serbian Vlade Divac, Lithuanians Arvydas Sabonis and Šarūnas Marčiulionis, Dutchman Rik Smits, and German Detlef Schrempf.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In the Philippines, the Philippine Basketball Association's first game was played on April 9, 1975, at the Araneta Coliseum in Cubao, Quezon City, Philippines.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] It was founded as a "rebellion" of several teams from the now-defunct Manila Industrial and Commercial Athletic Association, which was tightly controlled by the Basketball Association of the Philippines (now defunct), the then-FIBA recognized national association.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Nine teams from the MICAA participated in the league's first season that opened on April 9, 1975.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The NBL is Australia's pre-eminent men's professional basketball league.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The league commenced in 1979, playing a winter season (April–September) and did so until the completion of the 20th season in 1998.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The 1998–99 season, which commenced only months later, was the first season after the shift to the current summer season format (October–April).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] This shift was an attempt to avoid competing directly against Australia's various football codes.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] It features eight teams from around Australia and one in New Zealand.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A few players including Luc Longley, Andrew Gaze, Shane Heal, Chris Anstey, and Andrew Bogut made it big internationally, becoming poster figures for the sport in Australia.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The Women's National Basketball League began in 1981.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Women began to play basketball in the fall of 1892 at Smith College through Senda Berenson, substitute director of the newly opened gymnasium and physical education teacher, after having modified the rules for women.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Shortly after Berenson was hired at Smith, she visited Naismith to learn more about the game.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Fascinated by the new sport and the values it could teach, she instantly introduced the game as a class exercise and soon after teams were organized.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first women's collegiate basketball game was played on March 21, 1893, when her Smith freshmen and sophomores played against one another.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first official women's interinstitutional game was played later that year between the University of California and the Miss Head's School.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] These rules, designed by Berenson, were published in 1899.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1902 Berenson became the editor of A.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Spalding's first Women's Basketball Guide.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The same year women of Mount Holyoke and Sophie Newcomb College (coached by Clara Gregory Baer), began playing basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] By 1895, the game had spread to colleges across the country, including Wellesley, Vassar, and Bryn Mawr.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first intercollegiate women's game was on April 4, 1896.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Stanford women played Berkeley, 9-on-9, ending in a 2–1 Stanford victory.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Women's basketball development was more structured than that for men in the early years.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 1905, the executive committee on Basket Ball Rules (National Women's Basketball Committee) was created by the American Physical Education Association.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] These rules called for six to nine players per team and 11 officials.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The International Women's Sports Federation (1924) included a women's basketball competition.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] 37 women's high school varsity basketball or state tournaments were held by 1925.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] And in 1926, the Amateur Athletic Union backed the first national women's basketball championship, complete with men's rules.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The Edmonton Grads, a touring Canadian women's team based in Edmonton, Alberta, operated between 1915 and 1940.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The Grads toured all over North America, and were exceptionally successful.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] They posted a record of 522 wins and only 20 losses over that span, as they met any team that wanted to challenge them, funding their tours from gate receipts.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The Grads also shone on several exhibition trips to Europe, and won four consecutive exhibition Olympics tournaments, in 1924, 1928, 1932, and 1936; however, women's basketball was not an official Olympic sport until 1976.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The Grads' players were unpaid, and had to remain single.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The Grads' style focused on team play, without overly emphasizing skills of individual players.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The first women's AAU All-America team was chosen in 1929.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Women's industrial leagues sprang up throughout the United States, producing famous athletes, including Babe Didrikson of the Golden Cyclones, and the All American Red Heads Team, which competed against men's teams, using men's rules.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] By 1938, the women's national championship changed from a three-court game to two-court game with six players per team.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The NBA-backed Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA) began in 1997.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Though it had shaky attendance figures, several marquee players (Lisa Leslie, Diana Taurasi, Sue Bird, and Candace Parker among others) have helped the league's popularity and level of competition.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Other professional women's basketball leagues in the United States, such as the American Basketball League (1996–98), have folded in part because of the popularity of the WNBA.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The WNBA has been looked at by many as a niche league.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] However, the league has recently taken steps forward.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In June 2007, the WNBA signed a contract extension with ESPN.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The new television deal ran from 2009 to 2016.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Along with this deal, came the first-ever rights fees to be paid to a women's professional sports league.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Over the eight years of the contract, "millions and millions of dollars" were "dispersed to the league's teams." In a March 12, 2009, article, NBA commissioner David Stern said that in the bad economy, "the NBA is far less profitable than the WNBA.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] We're losing a lot of money among a large number of teams.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Measurements and time limits discussed in this section often vary among tournaments and organizations; international and NBA rules are used in this section.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The object of the game is to outscore one's opponents by throwing the ball through the opponents' basket from above while preventing the opponents from doing so on their own.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] An attempt to score in this way is called a shot.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A successful shot is worth two points, or three points if it is taken from beyond the three-point arc 6.75 meters (22 ft 2 in) from the basket in international games and 23 feet 9 inches (7.24 m) in NBA games.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A one-point shot can be earned when shooting from the foul line after a foul is made.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] After a team has scored from a field goal or free throw, play is resumed with a **throw-in** awarded to the non-scoring team taken from a point beyond the endline of the court where the points were scored.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Games are played in four quarters of 10 (FIBA) or 12 minutes (NBA).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] College men's games use two 20-minute halves, college women's games use 10-minute quarters, and most United States high school varsity games use 8-minute quarters; however, this varies from state to state.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] 15 minutes are allowed for a half-time break under FIBA, NBA, and NCAA rules and 10 minutes in United States high schools.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Overtime periods are five minutes in length except for high school, which is four minutes in length.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Teams exchange baskets for the second half.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The time allowed is actual playing time; the clock is stopped while the play is not active.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Therefore, games generally take much longer to complete than the allotted game time, typically about two hours.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Five players from each team may be on the court at one time.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Substitutions are unlimited but can only be done when play is stopped.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Teams also have a coach, who oversees the development and strategies of the team, and other team personnel such as assistant coaches, managers, statisticians, doctors and trainers.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] For both men's and women's teams, a standard uniform consists of a pair of shorts and a jersey with a clearly visible number, unique within the team, printed on both the front and back.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A limited number of time-outs, clock stoppages requested by a coach (or sometimes mandated in the NBA) for a short meeting with the players, are allowed.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] They generally last no longer than one minute (100 seconds in the NBA) unless, for televised games, a commercial break is needed.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The game is controlled by the officials consisting of the referee (referred to as crew chief in the NBA), one or two umpires (referred to as referees in the NBA) and the table officials.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] For college, the NBA, and many high schools, there are a total of three referees on the court.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The table officials are responsible for keeping track of each team's scoring, timekeeping, individual and team fouls, player substitutions, team possession arrow, and the shot clock.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The only essential equipment in a basketball game is the ball and the court: a flat, rectangular surface with baskets at opposite ends.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Competitive levels require the use of more equipment such as clocks, score sheets, scoreboards, alternating possession arrows, and whistle-operated stop-clock systems.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A regulation basketball court in international games is 28 meters (92 feet) long and 15 meters (49 feet) wide.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In the NBA and NCAA, the court is 94 by 50 feet (29 by 15 meters).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Most courts have wood flooring, usually constructed from maple planks running in the same direction as the longer court dimension.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The name and logo of the home team is usually painted on or around the center circle.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The basket is a steel rim 18 inches (46 cm) diameter with an attached net affixed to a backboard that measures 6 by 3.5 feet (1.8 by 1.1 meters) and one basket is at each end of the court.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The white outlined box on the backboard is 18 inches (46 cm) high and 2 feet (61 cm) wide.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] At almost all levels of competition, the top of the rim is exactly 10 feet (3.05 meters) above the court and 4 feet (1.22 meters) inside the baseline.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] While variation is possible in the dimensions of the court and backboard, it is considered important for the basket to be of the correct height – a rim that is off by just a few inches can have an adverse effect on shooting.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The net must "check the ball momentarily as it passes through the basket" to aid the visual confirmation that the ball went through.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The act of checking the ball has the further advantage of slowing down the ball so the rebound does not go as far.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The size of the basketball is also regulated.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] For men, the official ball is 29.5 inches (75 cm) in circumference (size 7, or a "295 ball") and weighs 22 oz (620 g).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] If women are playing, the official basketball size is 28.5 inches (72 cm) in circumference (size 6, or a "285 ball") with a weight of 20 oz (570 g).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In 3x3, a formalized version of the halfcourt 3-on-3 game, a dedicated ball with the circumference of a size 6 ball but the weight of a size 7 ball is used in all competitions (men's, women's, and mixed teams).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The ball may be advanced toward the basket by being shot, passed between players, thrown, tapped, rolled or dribbled (bouncing the ball while running).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The ball must stay within the court; the last team to touch the ball before it travels out of bounds forfeits possession.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The ball is out of bounds if it touches a boundary line, or touches any player or object that is out of bounds.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] There are limits placed on the steps a player may take without dribbling, which commonly results in an infraction known as traveling.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Nor may a player stop their dribble and then resume dribbling.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A dribble that touches both hands is considered stopping the dribble, giving this infraction the name double dribble.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Within a dribble, the player cannot carry the ball by placing their hand on the bottom of the ball; doing so is known as carrying the ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A team, once having established ball control in the front half of their court, may not return the ball to the backcourt and be the first to touch it.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A violation of these rules results in loss of possession.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The ball may not be kicked, nor be struck with the fist.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] For the offense, a violation of these rules results in loss of possession; for the defense, most leagues reset the shot clock and the offensive team is given possession of the ball out of bounds.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] These rules are designed to promote more offense.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] There are also limits on how players may block an opponent's field goal attempt or help a teammate's field goal attempt.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Goaltending is a defender's touching of a ball that is on a downward flight toward the basket, while the related violation of basket interference is the touching of a ball that is on the rim or above the basket, or by a player reaching through the basket from below.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Goaltending and basket interference committed by a defender result in awarding the basket to the offense, while basket interference committed by an offensive player results in cancelling the basket if one is scored.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The defense gains possession in all cases of goaltending or basket interference.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] An attempt to unfairly disadvantage an opponent through certain types of physical contact is illegal and is called a personal foul.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] These are most commonly committed by defensive players; however, they can be committed by offensive players as well.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Players who are fouled either receive the ball to pass inbounds again, or receive one or more free throws if they are fouled in the act of shooting, depending on whether the shot was successful.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] One point is awarded for making a free throw, which is attempted from a line 15 feet (4.6 m) from the basket.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The referee is responsible for judging whether contact is illegal, sometimes resulting in controversy.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] The calling of fouls can vary between games, leagues and referees.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] There is a second category of fouls called technical fouls, which may be charged for various rules violations including failure to properly record a player in the scorebook, or for unsportsmanlike conduct.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] These infractions result in one or two free throws, which may be taken by any of the five players on the court at the time.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] Repeated incidents can result in disqualification.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A blatant foul involving physical contact that is either excessive or unnecessary is called an intentional foul (flagrant foul in the NBA).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In FIBA and NCAA women's basketball, a foul resulting in ejection is called a disqualifying foul, while in leagues other than the NBA, such a foul is referred to as flagrant.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] If a team exceeds a certain limit of team fouls in a given period (quarter or half) – four for NBA, NCAA women's, and international games – the opposing team is awarded one or two free throws on all subsequent non-shooting fouls for that period, the number depending on the league.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In the US college men's game and high school games for both sexes, if a team reaches 7 fouls in a half, the opposing team is awarded one free throw, along with a second shot if the first is made.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] If a team exceeds 10 fouls in the half, the opposing team is awarded two free throws on all subsequent fouls for the half.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] When a team shoots foul shots, the opponents may not interfere with the shooter, nor may they try to regain possession until the last or potentially last free throw is in the air.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] After a team has committed a specified number of fouls, the other team is said to be "in the bonus".
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] On scoreboards, this is usually signified with an indicator light reading "Bonus" or "Penalty" with an illuminated directional arrow or dot indicating that team is to receive free throws when fouled by the opposing team.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] If a team misses the first shot of a two-shot situation, the opposing team must wait for the completion of the second shot before attempting to reclaim possession of the ball and continuing play.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] If a player is fouled while attempting a shot and the shot is unsuccessful, the player is awarded a number of free throws equal to the value of the attempted shot.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] A player fouled while attempting a regular two-point shot thus receives two shots, and a player fouled while attempting a three-point shot receives three shots.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] If a player is fouled while attempting a shot and the shot is successful, typically the player will be awarded one additional free throw for one point.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p01] In combination with a regular shot, this is called a "three-point play" or "four-point play" (or more colloquially, an "and one") because of the basket made at the time of the foul (2 or 3 points) and the additional free throw (1 point).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Although the rules do not specify any positions whatsoever, they have evolved as part of basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] During the early years of basketball's evolution, two guards, two forwards, and one center were used.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] In more recent times, specific positions evolved, but the current trend, advocated by many top coaches including Mike Krzyzewski, is towards positionless basketball, where big players are free to shoot from outside and dribble if their skill allows it.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Point guard (often called the "**1**") : usually the fastest player on the team, organizes the team's offense by controlling the ball and making sure that it gets to the right player at the right time.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Shooting guard (the "**2**") : creates a high volume of shots on offense, mainly long-ranged; and guards the opponent's best perimeter player on defense.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Small forward (the "**3**") : often primarily responsible for scoring points via cuts to the basket and dribble penetration; on defense seeks rebounds and steals, but sometimes plays more actively.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Power forward (the "**4**"): plays offensively often with their back to the basket; on defense, plays under the basket (in a zone defense) or against the opposing power forward (in man-to-man defense).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Center (the "**5**"): uses height and size to score (on offense), to protect the basket closely (on defense), or to rebound.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] There are two main defensive strategies: *zone defense* and *man-to-man defense*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] In a zone defense, each player is assigned to guard a specific area of the court.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Zone defenses often allow the defense to double team the ball, a maneuver known as a **trap**.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] In a man-to-man defense, each defensive player guards a specific opponent.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Offensive plays are more varied, normally involving planned passes and movement by players without the ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A quick movement by an offensive player without the ball to gain an advantageous position is known as a *cut*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A legal attempt by an offensive player to stop an opponent from guarding a teammate, by standing in the defender's way such that the teammate cuts next to him, is a *screen* or *pick*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The two plays are combined in the *pick and roll*, in which a player sets a pick and then "rolls" away from the pick towards the basket.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Screens and cuts are very important in offensive plays; these allow the quick passes and teamwork, which can lead to a successful basket.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Teams almost always have several offensive plays planned to ensure their movement is not predictable.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] On court, the point guard is usually responsible for indicating which play will occur.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Shooting is the act of attempting to score points by throwing the ball through the basket, methods varying with players and situations.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Typically, a player faces the basket with both feet facing the basket.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A player will rest the ball on the fingertips of the dominant hand (the shooting arm) slightly above the head, with the other hand supporting the side of the ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The ball is usually shot by jumping (though not always) and extending the shooting arm.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The shooting arm, fully extended with the wrist fully bent, is held stationary for a moment following the release of the ball, known as a *follow-through*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Players often try to put a steady backspin on the ball to absorb its impact with the rim.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The ideal trajectory of the shot is somewhat controversial, but generally a proper arc is recommended.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Players may shoot directly into the basket or may use the backboard to redirect the ball into the basket.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The two most common shots that use the above described setup are the *set shot* and the *jump shot*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Both are preceded by a crouching action which preloads the muscles and increases the power of the shot.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] In a set shot, the shooter straightens up and throws from a standing position with neither foot leaving the floor; this is typically used for free throws.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] For a jump shot, the throw is taken in mid-air with the ball being released near the top of the jump.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] This provides much greater power and range, and it also allows the player to elevate over the defender.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Failure to release the ball before the feet return to the floor is considered a traveling violation.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Another common shot is called the *layup*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] This shot requires the player to be in motion toward the basket, and to "lay" the ball "up" and into the basket, typically off the backboard (the backboard-free, underhand version is called a *finger roll*).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The most crowd-pleasing and typically highest-percentage accuracy shot is the *slam dunk*, in which the player jumps very high and throws the ball downward, through the basket while touching it.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Another shot, less common than the layup, is the "circus shot".
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The circus shot is a low-percentage shot that is flipped, heaved, scooped, or flung toward the hoop while the shooter is off-balance, airborne, falling down or facing away from the basket.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A back-shot is a shot taken when the player is facing away from the basket, and may be shot with the dominant hand, or both; but there is a very low chance that the shot will be successful.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A shot that misses both the rim and the backboard completely is referred to as an *air ball*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A particularly bad shot, or one that only hits the backboard, is jocularly called a brick.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The *hang time* is the length of time a player stays in the air after jumping, either to make a slam dunk, layup or jump shot.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The objective of rebounding is to successfully gain possession of the basketball after a missed field goal or free throw, as it rebounds from the hoop or backboard.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] This plays a major role in the game, as most possessions end when a team misses a shot.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] There are two categories of rebounds: offensive rebounds, in which the ball is recovered by the offensive side and does not change possession, and defensive rebounds, in which the defending team gains possession of the loose ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The majority of rebounds are defensive, as the team on defense tends to be in better position to recover missed shots; for example, about 75% of rebounds in the NBA are defensive.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A pass is a method of moving the ball between players.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Most passes are accompanied by a step forward to increase power and are followed through with the hands to ensure accuracy.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The ball is passed directly from the passer's chest to the receiver's chest.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A proper chest pass involves an outward snap of the thumbs to add velocity and leaves the defence little time to react.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Another type of pass is the *bounce pass*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Here, the passer bounces the ball crisply about two-thirds of the way from his own chest to the receiver.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The ball strikes the court and bounces up toward the receiver.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The bounce pass takes longer to complete than the chest pass, but it is also harder for the opposing team to intercept (kicking the ball deliberately is a violation).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Thus, players often use the bounce pass in crowded moments, or to pass around a defender.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The *overhead pass* is used to pass the ball over a defender.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The ball is released while over the passer's head.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The *outlet pass* occurs after a team gets a defensive rebound.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The next pass after the rebound is the *outlet pass*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The crucial aspect of any good pass is it being difficult to intercept.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Good passers can pass the ball with great accuracy and they know exactly where each of their other teammates prefers to receive the ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A special way of doing this is passing the ball without looking at the receiving teammate.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Another advanced style of passing is the *behind-the-back pass*, which, as the description implies, involves throwing the ball behind the passer's back to a teammate.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Although some players can perform such a pass effectively, many coaches discourage no-look or behind-the-back passes, believing them to be difficult to control and more likely to result in turnovers or violations.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Dribbling is the act of bouncing the ball continuously with one hand and is a requirement for a player to take steps with the ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] To dribble, a player pushes the ball down towards the ground with the fingertips rather than patting it; this ensures greater control.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] When dribbling past an opponent, the dribbler should dribble with the hand farthest from the opponent, making it more difficult for the defensive player to get to the ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] It is therefore important for a player to be able to dribble competently with both hands.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Good dribblers (or "ball handlers") tend to keep their dribbling hand low to the ground, reducing the distance of travel of the ball from the floor to the hand, making it more difficult for the defender to "steal" the ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Good ball handlers frequently dribble behind their backs, between their legs, and switch directions suddenly, making a less predictable dribbling pattern that is more difficult to defend against.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] This is called a crossover, which is the most effective way to move past defenders while dribbling.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A skilled player can dribble without watching the ball, using the dribbling motion or peripheral vision to keep track of the ball's location.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] By not having to focus on the ball, a player can look for teammates or scoring opportunities, as well as avoid the danger of having someone steal the ball away from him/her.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] A block is performed when, after a shot is attempted, a defender succeeds in altering the shot by touching the ball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] In almost all variants of play, it is illegal to touch the ball after it is in the downward path of its arc; this is known as *goaltending*.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] It is also illegal under the NBA and Men's NCAA basketball to block a shot after it has touched the backboard, or when any part of the ball is directly above the rim.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Under international rules it is illegal to block a shot that is in the downward path of its arc or one that has touched the backboard until the ball has hit the rim.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] After the ball hits the rim, it is again legal to touch it even though it is no longer considered as a block performed.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] To block a shot, a player has to be able to reach a point higher than where the shot is released.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Thus, height can be an advantage in blocking.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Players who are taller and playing the power forward or center positions generally record more blocks than players who are shorter and playing the guard positions.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] However, with good timing and a sufficiently high vertical leap, even shorter players can be effective shot blockers.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] At the professional level, most male players are above 6 feet 3 inches (1.91 m) and most women above 5 feet 7 inches (1.70 m).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Guards, for whom physical coordination and ball-handling skills are crucial, tend to be the smallest players.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Almost all forwards in the top men's pro leagues are 6 feet 6 inches (1.98 m) or taller.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Most centers are over 6 feet 10 inches (2.08 m) tall.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] According to a survey given to all NBA teams, the average height of all NBA players with shoes on is around 6 feet 6 inches (1.98 m), although exaggeration of height is widespread.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The average weight is close to 222 pounds (101 kg).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The tallest players ever in the NBA were Manute Bol and Gheorghe Mureșan, who were both 7 feet 7 inches (2.31 m) tall.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] At 7 feet 2 inches (2.18 m), Margo Dydek was the tallest player in the history of the WNBA.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The shortest player ever to play in the NBA is Muggsy Bogues at 5 feet 3 inches (1.60 m).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Other average-height or relatively short players have thrived at the pro level, including Anthony "Spud" Webb, who was 5 feet 7 inches (1.70 m) tall, but had a 42-inch (1.1 m) vertical leap, giving him significant height when jumping.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] There was also Yuki Kawamura, who stood at 5 ft 8 in (1.73 m), found success with the Japan men's national basketball team, with him averaging 20 points, 3 rebounds, and 7 assists with his team.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] His success with his national team led him to sign a two-way deal with the Memphis Grizzlies of the NBA.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Lastly, Temeka Johnson, who won the WNBA Rookie of the Year Award and a championship with the Phoenix Mercury while standing only 5 feet 3 inches (1.60 m).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] While shorter players are often at a disadvantage in certain aspects of the game, their ability to navigate quickly through crowded areas of the court and steal the ball by reaching low is a strength.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Players regularly inflate their height in high school or college.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Many prospects exaggerate their height while in high school or college to make themselves more appealing to coaches and scouts, who prefer taller players.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Charles Barkley stated; "I've been measured at 6–5, 6-4+3⁄4.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] But I started in college at 6–6." Sam Smith, a former writer from the *Chicago Tribune*, said: "We sort of know the heights, because after camp, the sheet comes out.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] But you use that height, and the player gets mad.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Or you file your story with the right height, and the copy desk changes it because they have the 'official' N.B.A. media guide, which is wrong.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Since the 2019–20 NBA season, heights of NBA players are recorded definitively by measuring players with their shoes off.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Variations of basketball are activities based on the game of basketball, using common basketball skills and equipment (primarily the ball and basket).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Some variations only have superficial rule changes, while others are distinct games with varying degrees of influence from basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Other variations include children's games, contests or activities meant to help players reinforce skills.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] An earlier version of basketball, played primarily by women and girls, was six-on-six basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Horseball is a game played on horseback where a ball is handled and points are scored by shooting it through a high net (approximately 1.5m×1.5m).
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The sport is like a combination of polo, rugby, and basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] There is even a form played on donkeys known as Donkey basketball, which has attracted criticism from animal rights groups.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Perhaps the single most common variation of basketball is the half-court game, played in informal settings without referees or strict rules.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Only one basket is used, and the ball must be "taken back" or "cleared" – passed or dribbled outside the three-point line each time possession of the ball changes from one team to the other.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Half-court games require less cardiovascular stamina, since players need not run back and forth a full court.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Half-court raises the number of players that can use a court or, conversely, can be played if there is an insufficient number to form full 5-on-5 teams.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Half-court basketball is usually played 1-on-1, 2-on-2, or 3-on-3.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The last of these variations is gradually gaining official recognition as 3x3, originally known as FIBA 33.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] It was first tested at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau and the first official tournaments were held at the 2009 Asian Youth Games and the 2010 Youth Olympics, both in Singapore.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The first FIBA 3x3 Youth World Championships were held in Rimini, Italy in 2011, with the first FIBA 3x3 World Championships for senior teams following a year later in Athens.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The sport is highly tipped to become an Olympic sport as early as 2016.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] In the summer of 2017, the BIG3 basketball league, a professional 3x3 half court basketball league that features former NBA players, began.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] The BIG3 features several rule variants including a four-point field goal.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Basketball as a social and communal sport features environments, rules and demographics different from those seen in professional and televised basketball.
[src:rewindpix/basketball-p02] Basketball is played widely as an extracurricular, intramural or amateur sport in schools and colleges.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Generally, the faster and volatile storage components are referred to as "memory", while slower persistent components are referred to as "storage".
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] This distinction was extended in the Von Neumann architecture, where the central processing unit (CPU) consists of two main parts: The control unit and the arithmetic logic unit (ALU).
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The former controls the flow of data between the CPU and memory, while the latter performs arithmetic and logical operations on data.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] In practice, almost all computers use a memory hierarchy, which puts memory close to the CPU and storage further away.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] In modern computers, hard disk drives (HDDs) or solid-state drives (SSDs) are usually used as storage.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] A modern digital computer represents data using the binary numeral system.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The memory cell is the fundamental building block of computer memory, storing stores one bit of binary information that can be set to store a 1, reset to store a 0, and accessed by reading the cell.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Text, numbers, pictures, audio, and nearly any other form of information can be converted into a string of bits, or binary digits, each of which has a value of 0 or 1.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The most common unit of storage is the byte, equal to 8 bits.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Digital data comprises the binary representation of a piece of information, often being encoded by assigning a bit pattern to each character, digit, or multimedia object.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Many standards exist for encoding (e.g. character encodings like ASCII, image encodings like JPEG, and video encodings like MPEG-4).
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] For security reasons, certain types of data may be encrypted in storage to prevent the possibility of unauthorized information reconstruction from chunks of storage snapshots.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Encryption in transit protects data as it is being transmitted.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Data compression methods allow in many cases (such as a database) to represent a string of bits by a shorter bit string ("compress") and reconstruct the original string ("decompress") when needed.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] This utilizes substantially less storage (tens of percent) for many types of data at the cost of more computation (compress and decompress when needed).
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Analysis of the trade-off between storage cost saving and costs of related computations and possible delays in data availability is done before deciding whether to keep certain data compressed or not.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Distinct types of data storage have different points of failure and various methods of predictive failure analysis.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Vulnerabilities that can instantly lead to total loss are head crashing on mechanical hard drives and failure of electronic components on flash storage.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Redundancy allows the computer to detect errors in coded data (for example, a random bit flip due to random radiation) and correct them based on mathematical algorithms.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The cyclic redundancy check (CRC) method is typically used in communications and storage for error detection.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Redundancy solutions include storage replication, disk mirroring and RAID (Redundant Array of Independent Disks).
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Impending failure on hard disk drives is estimable using S.M.A.R.T. diagnostic data that includes the hours of operation and the count of spin-ups, though its reliability is disputed.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The health of optical media can be determined by measuring correctable minor errors, of which high counts signify deteriorating and/or low-quality media.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Too many consecutive minor errors can lead to data corruption.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Not all vendors and models of optical drives support error scanning.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Without a significant amount of memory, a computer would only be able to perform fixed operations and immediately output the result, thus requiring hardware reconfiguration for a new program to be run.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] This is often used in devices such as desk calculators, digital signal processors, and other specialized devices.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Von Neumann machines differ in having a memory in which operating instructions and data are stored, such that they do not need to have their hardware reconfigured for each new program, but can simply be reprogrammed with new in-memory instructions.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] They also tend to be simpler to design, in that a relatively simple processor may keep state between successive computations to build up complex procedural results.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Most modern computers are von Neumann machines.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] In contemporary usage, the term "storage" typically refers to a subset of computer data storage that comprises storage devices and their media not directly accessible by the CPU, that is, secondary or tertiary storage.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Common forms of storage include hard disk drives, optical disc drives, and non-volatile devices (i.e. devices that retain their contents when the computer is powered down).
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] On the other hand, the term "memory" is used to refer to semiconductor read-write data storage, typically dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Dynamic random-access memory is a form of volatile memory that also requires the stored information to be periodically reread and rewritten, or refreshed; static RAM (SRAM) is similar to DRAM, albeit it never needs to be refreshed as long as power is applied.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] In contemporary usage, the memory hierarchy of primary storage and secondary storage in some uses refer to what was historically called, respectively, *secondary storage* and *tertiary storage*.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] This led to modern random-access memory, which is small-sized, light, and relatively expensive.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] RAM used for primary storage is volatile, meaning that it loses the information when not powered for a specific time.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Besides storing opened programs, it serves as disk cache and write buffer to improve both reading and writing performance.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Operating systems borrow RAM capacity for caching so long as it's not needed by running software.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Spare memory can be utilized as RAM drive for temporary high-speed data storage.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Primary storage, including ROM, EEPROM, NOR flash, and RAM, is usually byte-addressable.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Such memory is directly or indirectly connected to the central processing unit via a memory bus, comprising an address bus and a data bus.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The CPU firstly sends a number called the memory address through the address bus that indicates the desired location of data.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Then it reads or writes the data in the memory cells using the data bus.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Additionally, a memory management unit (MMU) is a small device between CPU and RAM recalculating the actual memory address.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Memory management units allow for memory management; they may, for example, provide an abstraction of virtual memory or other tasks.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Non-volatile primary storage containing a small startup program (BIOS) is used to bootstrap the computer, that is, to read a larger program from non-volatile secondary storage to RAM and start to execute it.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] A non-volatile technology used for this purpose is called read-only memory (ROM).
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Most types of "ROM" are not literally read only but are difficult and slow to write to*.* Some embedded systems run programs directly from ROM, because such programs are rarely changed.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Standard computers largely do not store many programs in ROM, apart from firmware, and use large capacities of secondary storage.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] In modern computers, hard disk drives (HDDs) or solid-state drives (SSDs) are usually used as secondary storage.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The access time per byte for HDDs or SSDs is typically measured in milliseconds, while the access time per byte for primary storage is measured in nanoseconds.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Rotating optical storage devices, such as CD and DVD drives, have even longer access times.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Other examples of secondary storage technologies include USB flash drives, floppy disks, magnetic tape, paper tape, punched cards, and RAM disks.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] To reduce the seek time and rotational latency, secondary storage, including HDD, ODD and SSD, are transferred to and from disks in large contiguous blocks.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Secondary storage is addressable by block; once the disk read/write head on HDDs reaches the proper placement and the data, subsequent data on the track are very fast to access.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Another way to reduce the I/O bottleneck is to use multiple disks in parallel to increase the bandwidth between primary and secondary memory, for example, using RAID.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Secondary storage is often formatted according to a file system format, which provides the abstraction necessary to organize data into files and directories, while also providing metadata describing the owner of a certain file, the access time, the access permissions, and other information.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Most computer operating systems use the concept of virtual memory, allowing the utilization of more primary storage capacity than is physically available in the system.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] As the primary memory fills up, the system moves the least-used chunks (pages) to a swap file or page file on secondary storage, retrieving them later when needed.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] A secondary or tertiary storage may connect to a computer utilizing computer networks.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] This concept does not pertain to the primary storage.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Cloud storage is based on highly virtualized infrastructure.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] A subset of cloud computing, it has particular cloud-native interfaces, near-instant elasticity and scalability, multi-tenancy, and metered resources.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Cloud storage services can be used from an off-premises service or deployed on-premises.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Cloud deployment models define the interactions between cloud providers and customers.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Storage technologies at all levels of the storage hierarchy can be differentiated by evaluating certain core characteristics as well as measuring characteristics specific to a particular implementation.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Semiconductor memory uses semiconductor-based integrated circuit (IC) chips to store information.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Data are typically stored in metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) memory cells.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] A semiconductor memory chip may contain millions of memory cells, consisting of tiny MOS field-effect transistors (MOSFETs) and/or MOS capacitors.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Both *volatile* and *non-volatile* forms of semiconductor memory exist, the former using standard MOSFETs and the latter using floating-gate MOSFETs.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] In modern computers, primary storage almost exclusively consists of dynamic volatile semiconductor random-access memory (RAM), particularly dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Since the turn of the century, a type of non-volatile floating-gate semiconductor memory known as flash memory has steadily gained share as off-line storage for home computers.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Non-volatile semiconductor memory is also used for secondary storage in various advanced electronic devices and specialized computers that are designed for them.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] As early as 2006, notebook and desktop computer manufacturers started using flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) as default configuration options for the secondary storage either in addition to or instead of the more traditional HDD.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Magnetic storage uses different patterns of magnetization on a magnetically coated surface to store information.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The information is accessed using one or more read/write heads which may contain one or more recording transducers.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] A read/write head only covers a part of the surface so that the head or medium or both must be moved relative to another in order to access data.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Magnetic storage does not have a definite limit of rewriting cycles like flash storage and re-writeable optical media, as altering magnetic fields causes no physical wear.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Rather, their life span is limited by mechanical parts.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Optical storage, the typical optical disc, stores information in deformities on the surface of a circular disc and reads this information by illuminating the surface with a laser diode and observing the reflection.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The deformities may be permanent (read only media), formed once (write once media) or reversible (recordable or read/write media).
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Magneto-optical disc storage is optical disc storage where the magnetic state on a ferromagnetic surface stores information.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] The information is read optically and written by combining magnetic and optical methods.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Magneto-optical disc storage is *non-volatile*, *sequential access*, slow write, fast read storage used for tertiary and off-line storage.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] 3D optical data storage has also been proposed.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Light induced magnetization melting in magnetic photoconductors has also been proposed for high-speed low-energy consumption magneto-optical storage.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Paper data storage, typically in the form of paper tape or punched cards, has long been used to store information for automatic processing, particularly before general-purpose computers existed.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Information was recorded by punching holes into the paper or cardboard medium and was read mechanically (or later optically) to determine whether a particular location on the medium was solid or contained a hole.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Barcodes make it possible for objects that are sold or transported to have some computer-readable information securely attached.
[src:rewindpix/computer-storage] Relatively small amounts of digital data (compared to other digital data storage) may be backed up on paper as a matrix barcode for very long-term storage, as the longevity of paper typically exceeds even magnetic data storage.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A **digital camera**, also called a **digicam**, is a camera that uses digital storage to capture images.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most cameras produced since the start of the 21st century are digital, largely replacing cameras that captured images on photographic film or film stock.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras are now integrated into mobile devices such as smartphones.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] However, high-end dedicated digital cameras are still commonly used by professionals.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Digital cameras typically use a lens with an alterable diaphragm to focus light.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The diaphragm and shutter work to admit a controlled amount of light to the image.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] This process is the same as previously-used film cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] However, digital cameras use an image pickup device that is electronic, compared to chemical.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Additionally, digital cameras can display images on a screen immediately after being recorded, and store and delete images from stored memory.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras can also record moving videos with sound.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some digital cameras have the ability to crop and stitch pictures and perform other kinds of image editing.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The first semiconductor image sensor was the charge-coupled device (CCD), invented by Willard S.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Smith at Bell Labs in 1969, based on MOS capacitor technology.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The NMOS active-pixel sensor was later invented by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985, which led to the development of the CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Lally of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory was thinking about how to use a mosaic photo sensor to capture digital images.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] His idea was to take pictures of the planets and stars while travelling through space to give information about the astronauts' position.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] As with Texas Instruments employee Willis Adcock's filmless camera (US patent 4,057,830) in 1972, the technology had yet to catch up with the concept.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 1972, the Landsat 1 satellite's multispectral scanner (MSS) started taking digital images of Earth.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The MSS, designed by Virginia Norwood at Hughes Aircraft Company starting in 1969, captured and transmitted image data from green, red, and two infrared bands with 6 bits per channel, using a mechanical rocking mirror and an array of 24 detectors.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Operating for six years, it transmitted more than 300,000 digital photographs of Earth while orbiting the planet about 14 times per day.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Also in 1972, Thomas McCord from MIT and James Westphal from Caltech together developed a digital camera for use with telescopes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Their 1972 "photometer-digitizer system" used an analog-to-digital converter and a digital frame memory to store 256 x 256-pixel images of planets and stars, which were then recorded on digital magnetic tape.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] CCD sensors were not yet commercially available, and the camera used a silicon diode vidicon tube detector, which was cooled using dry ice to reduce dark current, allowing exposure times of up to one hour.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The Cromemco Cyclops was an all-digital camera introduced as a commercial product in 1975.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Its design was published as a hobbyist construction project in the February 1975 issue of *Popular Electronics* magazine.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] It used a 32×32 metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) image sensor, which was a modified MOS dynamic RAM (DRAM) memory chip.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Steven Sasson, an engineer at Eastman Kodak, built a self-contained electronic camera that used a monochrome Fairchild Semiconductor CCD image sensor in 1975.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Around the same time, Fujifilm began developing CCD technology in the 1970s.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Early uses were mainly military and scientific, followed by medical and news applications.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The first filmless SLR (single lens reflex) camera was publicly demonstrated by Sony in August 1981.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The Sony Mavica (magnetic still video camera) used a color-striped 2/3" format CCD sensor with 280K pixels, along with analogue video signal processing and recording.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The Mavica electronic still camera recorded FM-modulated analog video signals on a newly developed 2" magnetic floppy disk, dubbed the "Mavipak".
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The disk format was later standardized as the "Still Video Floppy", or "SVF".
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The Canon RC-701, introduced in May 1986, was the first SVF camera (and the first electronic SLR camera) sold in the US.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] It employed an SLR viewfinder, included a 2/3" format color CCD sensor with 380K pixels, and was sold along with a removable 11-66mm and 50-150mm zoom lens.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Over the next few years, many other companies began selling SVF cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] These analog electronic cameras included the Nikon QV-1000C, which had an SLR viewfinder and a 2/3" format monochrome CCD sensor with 380K pixels and recorded analog black-and-white images on a Still Video Floppy.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] At Photokina 1988, Fujifilm introduced the FUJIX DS-1P, the first fully digital camera, which recorded digital images using a semiconductor memory card.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The camera's memory card had a capacity of 2 MB of SRAM (static random-access memory) and could hold up to ten photographs.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 1989, Fujifilm released the FUJIX DS-X, the first fully digital camera to be commercially released.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 1996, Toshiba's 40 MB flash memory card was adopted for several digital cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The first prototype camera phones were included in Isaac (camera phone), a personal digital assistant for people with intellectual disabilities which was deployed in 1994.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The first commercially available camera phone was the Kyocera Visual Phone VP-210, released in Japan in May 1999.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] It was called a "mobile videophone" at the time, and had a 110,000-pixel front-facing camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] It stored up to 20 JPEG digital images, which could be sent over e-mail, or the phone could send up to two images per second over Japan's Personal Handy-phone System (PHS) cellular network.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The Samsung SCH-V200, released in South Korea in June 2000, was also one of the first phones with a built-in camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] It had a TFT liquid-crystal display (LCD) and stored up to 20 digital photos at 350,000-pixel resolution.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] However, it could not send the resulting image over the telephone function but required a computer connection to access photos.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The first mass-market camera phone was the J-SH04, a Sharp J-Phone model sold in Japan in November 2000.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] It could instantly transmit pictures via cell phone telecommunication.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] By the mid-2000s, higher-end cell phones had an integrated digital camera, and by the early 2010s, almost all smartphones had an integrated digital camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In the early 2020's, a revival of digital cameras produced from the early 2000s that were produced prior to smartphones occurred as a TikTok trend and spread to other online marketplaces such as eBay and Etsy.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The trend was characterized by Gen Z nostalgia and a homage to the Y2K aesthetic.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The two major types of digital image sensors are CCD and CMOS.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A CCD sensor has one amplifier for all the pixels, while each pixel in a CMOS active-pixel sensor has its own amplifier.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Compared to CCDs, CMOS sensors use less power.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with a small sensor use a back-side-illuminated CMOS (BSI-CMOS) sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The image processing capabilities of the camera determine the outcome of the final image quality much more than the sensor type.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The resolution of a digital camera is often limited by the image sensor that turns light into discrete signals.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The brighter the image at a given point on the sensor, the larger the value that is read for that pixel.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Depending on the physical structure of the sensor, a color filter array may be used, which requires demosaicing to recreate a full-color image.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The number of pixels in the sensor determines the camera's "pixel count".
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In a typical sensor, the pixel count is the product of the number of rows and the number of columns.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] For example, a 1,000 by 1,000-pixel sensor would have 1,000,000 pixels, or 1 megapixel.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Firmwares' resolution selector allows the user to optionally lower the resolution to reduce the file size per picture and extend lossless digital zooming.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The bottom resolution option is typically 640×480 pixels (0.3 megapixels).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] An image's sharpness is presented through the crisp detail, defined lines, and its depicted contrast.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Sharpness is a factor of multiple systems throughout the DSLR camera by its ISO, resolution, lens, and the lens settings, the environment of the image, and its post-processing.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Images have a possibility of being too sharp, but they can never be too in focus.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A digital camera resolution is determined by a digital sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The digital sensor indicates a high level of sharpness can be produced through the amount of noise and grain that is tolerated through the lens of the camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Resolution within the field of digital stills and digital movies is indicated through the camera's ability to determine detail based on the distance, which is then measured by frame size, pixel type, number, and organization.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Although some DSLR cameras have limited resolutions, it is almost impossible to not have the proper sharpness for an image.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The ISO choice when taking a photo affects the quality of the image, as high ISO settings equate to an image that is less sharp due to the increased amount of noise allowed into the image, along with too little noise, which can also produce an image that is not sharp.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Since the first digital backs were introduced, there have been three main methods of capturing the image, each based on the hardware configuration of the sensor and color filters.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The third method is called *scanning* because the sensor moves across the focal plane much like the sensor of an image scanner.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The *linear* or *tri-linear* sensors in scanning cameras use only a single line of photosensors, or three lines for the three colors.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Scanning may be accomplished by moving the sensor (for example, when using color co-site sampling) or by rotating the whole camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A digital rotating line camera offers images consisting of a total resolution that is very high.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Improvements in single-shot cameras and image file processing at the beginning of the 21st century made single-shot cameras almost completely dominant, even in high-end commercial photography.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most current consumer digital cameras use a Bayer filter mosaic in combination with an optical anti-aliasing filter to reduce the aliasing due to the reduced sampling of the different primary-color images.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A demosaicing algorithm is used to interpolate color information to create a full array of RGB image data.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Cameras that use a beam-splitter single-shot 3CCD approach, three-filter multi-shot approach, color co-site sampling or Foveon X3 sensor do not use anti-aliasing filters, nor demosaicing.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A single sensor element cannot simultaneously record these three intensities, so a color filter array (CFA) must be used to selectively filter a particular color for each pixel.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The Bayer filter pattern is a repeating 2x2 mosaic pattern of light filters, with green ones at opposite corners and red and blue in the other two positions.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The high proportion of green takes advantage of the properties of the human visual system, which determines brightness mostly from green and is far more sensitive to brightness than to hue or saturation.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Sometimes a 4-color filter pattern is used, often involving two different hues of green.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] That provides potentially more accurate color, but requires a slightly more complicated interpolation process.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The color intensity values not captured for each pixel can be interpolated from the values of adjacent pixels which represent the color being calculated.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with digital image sensors that are smaller than the typical 35 mm film size have a smaller field or angle of view when used with a lens of the same focal length.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] This is because the angle of view is a function of both focal length and the sensor or film size used.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The crop factor is relative to the 35mm film format.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] If a smaller sensor is used, as in most digicams, the field of view is cropped by the sensor to smaller than the 35 mm full-frame format's field of view.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] This narrowing of the field of view may be described as crop factor, a factor by which a longer focal length lens would be needed to get the same field of view on a 35 mm film camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Full-frame digital SLRs use a sensor of the same size as a frame of 35 mm film.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Crop factors for non-SLR consumer compact and bridge cameras are larger, frequently 4x or more.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The resolution of a digital camera is often limited by the image sensor which turns light into discrete signals.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] **Pixels are square and is often equal to 1**, for example, a 1,000 by 1,000-pixel sensor would have 1,000,000 pixels, or 1 megapixel.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] On full-frame sensors (i.e., 24 mm 36 mm), some cameras propose images with 20–25 million pixels that were captured by 7.5–m photosites, or a surface that is 50 times larger.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Digital cameras come in a wide range of sizes, prices, and capabilities.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In addition to general-purpose digital cameras, specialized cameras including multispectral imaging equipment and astrographs are used for scientific, military, medical, and other special purposes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Compact cameras are intended to be portable (pocketable) and are particularly suitable for casual "snapshots".
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Point-and-shoot cameras usually fall under this category.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many incorporate a retractable lens assembly that provides optical zoom.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In most models, an auto-actuating lens cover protects the lens from elements.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most ruggedized or water-resistant models do not retract, and most with superzoom capability do not retract fully.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Compact cameras are usually designed to be easy to use.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Almost all include an automatic mode, or "auto mode", which automatically makes all camera settings for the user.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Compact digital cameras typically contain a small sensor that trades-off picture quality for compactness and simplicity; images can usually only be stored using lossy compression (JPEG).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most have a built-in flash usually of low power, sufficient for nearby subjects.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A few high-end compact digital cameras have a hot shoe for connecting to an external flash.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Live preview is almost always used to frame the photo on an integrated LCD.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In addition to being able to take still photographs almost all compact cameras have the ability to record video.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Compacts often have macro capability and zoom lenses, but the zoom range (up to 30x) is generally enough for candid photography but less than is available on bridge cameras (more than 60x), or the interchangeable lenses of DSLR cameras available at a much higher cost.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Autofocus systems in compact digital cameras generally are based on a contrast-detection methodology using the image data from the live preview feed of the main imager.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some compact digital cameras use a hybrid autofocus system similar to what is commonly available on DSLRs.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Typically, compact digital cameras incorporate a nearly silent leaf shutter into the lens but play a simulated camera sound for skeuomorphic purposes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] For low cost and small size, the cameras typically use image sensor formats with a diagonal between 6 and 11 mm, corresponding to a crop factor between 7 and 4.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] This gives them weaker low-light performance, greater depth of field, generally closer focusing ability, and smaller components than cameras using larger sensors.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some cameras use a larger sensor including, at the high end, a pricey full-frame sensor compact camera, such as Sony Cyber-shot DSC-RX1, but have the capability near that of a DSLR.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A variety of additional features are available depending on the model of the camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Such features include GPS, compass, barometers and altimeters.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Starting in 2010, some compact digital cameras can take 3D still photos.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] These 3D compact stereo cameras are able to capture 3D panoramic photos with dual lens or even a single lens for playback on a 3D TV.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2013, Sony released two add-on camera models without display, to be used with a smartphone or tablet, controlled by a mobile application via WiFi.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Rugged compact cameras typically include protection against submersion, hot and cold conditions, shock, and pressure.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Terms used to describe such properties include waterproof, freeze-proof, heatproof, shockproof, and crushproof, respectively.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Nearly all major camera manufacturers have at least one product in this category.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some are waterproof to a considerable depth up to 100 feet (30 m); others only 10 feet (3 m), but only a few will float.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Ruggeds often lack some of the features of ordinary compact camera, but they have video capability and the majority can record sound.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most have image stabilization and built-in flash.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Touchscreen LCD and GPS do not work underwater.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] GoPro and other brands offer action cameras which are rugged, small, and can be easily attached to helmets, arms, bicycles, etc.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most have a wide angle and fixed focus and can take still pictures and video, typically with sound.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The 360-degree camera can take picture or video 360 degrees using two lenses back-to-back and shooting at the same time.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some of the cameras are Ricoh Theta S, Nikon Keymission 360 and Samsung Gear 360.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Nico360 was launched in 2016 and claimed as the world's smallest 360-degree camera with size 46 x 46 x 28 mm (1.8 x 1.8 x 1.1 in) and price less than $200.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] With virtual reality mode built-in stitching, Wifi, and Bluetooth, live streaming can be done.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Due to it also being water resistant, the Nico360 can be used as action camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Bridge cameras physically resemble DSLRs, and are sometimes called DSLR-shape or DSLR-like.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] They provide some similar features but, like compacts, they use a fixed lens and a small sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some compact cameras have also PSAM mode.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most use live preview to frame the image.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Their usual autofocus is by the same contrast-detect mechanism as compacts, but many bridge cameras have a manual focus mode and some have a separate focus ring for greater control.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The big physical size and small sensor allow superzoom and wide aperture.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Bridge cameras generally include an image stabilization system to enable longer handheld exposures, sometimes better than DSLR for low light conditions.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Sony RX10) or 400 mm (variable aperture, e.g.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Panasonic Lumix FZ1000) equivalent, corresponding to an optical zoom factor of roughly 10 to 15.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some bridge cameras have a lens thread to attach accessories such as wide-angle or telephoto converters as well as filters such as UV or Circular Polarizing filter and lens hoods.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The scene is composed by viewing the display or the electronic viewfinder (EVF).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most have a slightly longer shutter lag than a DSLR.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many of these cameras can store images in a raw format in addition to supporting JPEG.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The majority have a built-in flash, but only a few have a hotshoe.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In bright sun, the quality difference between a good compact camera and a digital SLR is minimal but bridge cameras are more portable, cost less and have a greater zoom ability.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Thus a bridge camera may better suit outdoor daytime activities, except when seeking professional-quality photos.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In late 2008, a new type of camera emerged, called a *mirrorless interchangeable-lens camera*.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] It is technically a DSLR camera that does not require a reflex mirror, a key component of the former.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] While a typical DSLR has a mirror that reflects light from the lens up to the optical viewfinder, in a mirrorless camera, there is no optical viewfinder.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The image sensor is exposed to light at all times, giving the user a digital preview of the image either on the built-in rear LCD screen or an electronic viewfinder (EVF).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] These are simpler and more compact than DSLRs due to not having a lens reflex system.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some MILCs have a separate electronic viewfinder to compensate the lack of an optical one.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In other cameras, the back display is used as the primary viewfinder in the same way as in compact cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] One disadvantage of mirrorless cameras compared to a typical DSLR is its battery life due to the energy consumption of the electronic viewfinder, but this can be mitigated by a setting inside the camera in some models.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Olympus and Panasonic released many Micro Four-Thirds cameras with interchangeable lenses that are fully compatible with each other without any adapter, while others have proprietary mounts.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2014, Kodak released its first Micro Four Third system camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] As of March 2014, mirrorless cameras are fast becoming appealing to both amateurs and professionals alike due to their simplicity, compatibility with some DSLR lenses, and features that match most DSLRs today.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] While most digital cameras with interchangeable lenses feature a lens-mount of some kind, there are also a number of modular cameras, where the shutter and sensor are incorporated into the lens module.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The first such modular camera was the Minolta Dimâge V in 1996, followed by the Minolta Dimâge EX 1500 in 1998 and the Minolta MetaFlash 3D 1500 in 1999.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2009, Ricoh released the Ricoh GXR modular camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] At CES 2013, Sakar International announced the Polaroid iM1836, an 18MP camera with 1"-sensor with interchangeable sensor-lens.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] An adapter for Micro Four-Thirds, Nikon and K-mount lenses was planned to ship with the camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] There are also a number of add-on camera modules for smartphones, they are called *lens-style* cameras (lens camera or smart lens).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] They contain all the essential components of a digital camera inside a DSLR lens-shaped module, hence the name, but lack any sort of viewfinder and most controls of a regular camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Instead, they are connected wirelessly and/or mounted to a smartphone to be used as its display output and operate the camera's various controls.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLR) is a camera with a digital sensor that uses a reflex mirror to split or direct light into the viewfinder to produce an image.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The reflex mirror finds the image by blocking light to the camera's sensor and then reflecting it into the camera's pentaprism which allows it to be seen through the viewfinder.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] When the shutter release is fully pressed the reflex mirror pulls out horizontally below the pentaprism briefly darkening the viewfinder and then opening up the sensor for exposure which creates the photo.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The digital image is produced by the sensor which is an array of photoreceptors on a microchip capable of recording light values.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many modern DSLRs offer the ability for "live view" or the framing of the subject emitted from the sensor onto a digital screen, and many have a hotshoe.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The sensor also known as a **full-frame sensor** is much larger than the other types, typically 18mm to 36mm on the diagonal (crop factor 2, 1.6, or 1).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The larger sensor permits more light to be received by each pixel; this, combined with the relatively large lenses provides superior low-light performance.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] For the same field of view and the same aperture, a larger sensor gives shallower focus.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] DSLRs can equip interchangeable lenses for versatility by removing it from the lens mount of the camera, typically a silver ring on the front side of DSLRs.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] These lenses work in tandem with the mechanics of the DSLR to adjust aperture and focus.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Autofocus is accomplished using sensors in the mirror box and on most modern lenses can be activated from the lens itself which will trigger upon shutter release.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2025, a variety of lower-cost medium format digital cameras were available in the 50 to 100MP resolution range.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Digital Still Camera (DSC), such as the Sony DSC cameras, is a type of camera that does not use a reflex mirror.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] DSCs are like point-and-shoot cameras and are the most common type of cameras, due to their comfortable price and its quality.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with fixed semi-transparent mirrors, also known as DSLT cameras, such as the Sony SLT cameras, are single-lens without a moving reflex mirror as in a conventional DSLR.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A semi-transparent mirror transmits some of the light to the image sensor and reflects some of the light along the path to an autofocus sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The total amount of light is not changed, just some of the light travels one path and some of it travels the other.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The consequences are that DSLT cameras should shoot a half stop differently from DSLR.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] One advantage of using a DSLT camera is the blind moments a DSLR user experiences while the reflecting mirror is moved to send the light to the sensor instead of the viewfinder.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The "blackouts" do not exist for DSLT cameras since they use an EVF (electronic viewfinder).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Since there is no time at which light is not traveling along both paths, DSLT cameras get the benefit of continuous autofocus tracking.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] This is especially beneficial for burst-mode shooting in low-light conditions and also for tracking when taking video.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A rangefinder is a device to measure subject distance, with the intent to adjust the focus of a camera's objective lens accordingly (open-loop controller).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The rangefinder and lens focusing mechanism may or may not be coupled.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In common parlance, the term "rangefinder camera" is interpreted very narrowly to denote manual-focus cameras with a visually-read out optical rangefinder based on parallax.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most digital cameras achieve focus through analysis of the image captured by the objective lens and distance estimation, if it is provided at all, is only a byproduct of the focusing process (closed-loop controller).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A line-scan camera traditionally has a single row of pixel sensors, instead of a matrix of them.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The lines are continuously fed to a computer that joins them to each other and makes an image.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] That is most commonly done by connecting the camera output to a frame grabber which resides in a PCI slot of an industrial computer.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The frame grabber acts to buffer the image and sometimes provide some processing before delivering to the computer software for processing.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Industrial processes often require height and width measurements performed by digital line-scan systems.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Multiple rows of sensors may be used to make colored images, or to increase sensitivity by TDI (time delay and integration).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many industrial applications require a wide field of view.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Traditionally maintaining consistent light over large 2D areas is quite difficult.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] With a line scan camera all that is necessary is to provide even illumination across the "line" currently being viewed by the camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] This makes sharp pictures of objects that pass the camera at high speed.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Such cameras are also commonly used to make photo finishes, to determine the winner when multiple competitors cross the finishing line at nearly the same time.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] They can also be used as industrial instruments for analyzing fast processes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Line-scan cameras are also extensively used in imaging from satellites (see push broom scanner).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In this case the row of sensors is perpendicular to the direction of satellite motion.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Line-scan cameras are widely used in scanners.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In this case, the camera moves horizontally.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Superzoom cameras are cameras fitted with a variable focal length lens, typically ranging from a wide-angle focal length to a super-telephoto focal length.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] This type of digital camera captures information about the light field emanating from a scene; that is the intensity of light in a scene, and also the direction that the light rays are traveling in space.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] This contrasts with a conventional digital camera, which records only light intensity.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Instead of measuring the intensity of light over some predetermined time interval (the exposure time), event cameras detect when the intensity of light changes by some threshold for each pixel independently, usually with microsecond precision.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many devices have a built-in digital camera, including, for example, smartphones, mobile phones, PDAs and laptop computers.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Built-in cameras generally store the images in the JPEG file format, although cameras in Apple's iPhone line have used the HEIC format since 2017.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Mobile phones incorporating digital cameras were introduced in Japan in 2001 by J-Phone.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2003 camera phones outsold stand-alone digital cameras, and in 2006 they outsold film and digital stand-alone cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Five billion camera phones were sold in five years, and by 2007 more than half of the installed base of all mobile phones were camera phones.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Sales of separate cameras peaked in 2008.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Several manufacturers lead in digital camera (commonly DSLRs) production.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Each brand embodies different mission statements that differentiate it from the others besides the equipment it manufactures.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Most manufacturers share modern features in the cameras they produce.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] However, some specialize in specific details, either physically on camera or within the system and image quality.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Sales of traditional digital cameras have declined due to the increasing use of smartphones for casual photography, which also enable easier manipulation and sharing of photos through the use of apps and web-based services.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] "Bridge cameras", in contrast, have held their ground with functionality that most smartphone cameras lack, such as optical zoom and other advanced features.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] DSLRs have also lost ground to Mirrorless interchangeable-lens camera (MILC)s offering the same sensor size in a smaller camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A few expensive ones use a full-frame sensor, just like DSLR professional cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In response to the convenience and flexibility of smartphone cameras, some manufacturers produced "smart" digital cameras that combine features of traditional cameras with those of a smartphone.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2012, Nikon and Samsung released the Coolpix S800c and Galaxy Camera, the first two digital cameras to run the Android operating system.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Since this software platform is used in many smartphones, they can integrate with some of the same services (such as e-mail attachments, social networks and photo sharing sites) that smartphones do and use other Android-compatible software.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In an inversion, some phone makers have introduced smartphones with cameras designed to resemble traditional digital cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Nokia released the 808 PureView and Lumia 1020 in 2012 and 2013; the two devices respectively run the Symbian and Windows Phone operating systems, and both include a 41-megapixel camera (along with a camera grip attachment for the latter).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Similarly, Samsung introduced the Galaxy S4 Zoom, having a 16-megapixel camera and 10x optical zoom, combining traits from the Galaxy S4 Mini with the Galaxy Camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Panasonic Lumix DMC-CM1 is an Android KitKat 4.4 smartphone with 20MP, 1" sensor, the largest sensor for a smartphone ever, with Leica fixed lens equivalent of 28 mm at F2.8, can take RAW image and 4K video, has 21 mm thickness.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Furthermore, in 2018 Huawei P20 Pro is an android Oreo 8.1 has triple Leica lenses in the back of the smartphone with 40MP 1/1.7" RGB sensor as first lens, 20MP 1/2.7" monochrome sensor as second lens and 8MP 1/4" RGB sensor with 3x optical zoom as third lens.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Combination of first lens and second lens will produce bokeh image with larger high dynamic range, whereas combination of mega pixel first lens and optical zoom will produce maximum 5x digital zoom without loss of quality by reducing the image size to 8MP.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] After a big dip of sales in 2012, consumer digital camera sales declined again in 2013 by 36 percent.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2011, compact digital cameras sold 10 million per month.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2013, sales fell to about 4 million per month.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] DSLR and MILC sales also declined in 2013 by 10–15% after almost ten years of double digit growth.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Worldwide unit sales of digital cameras is continuously declining from 148 million in 2011 to 58 million in 2015 and tends to decrease more in the following years.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Film camera sales hit their peak at about 37 million units in 1997, while digital camera sales began in 1989.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] By 2008, the film camera market had died and digital camera sales hit their peak at 121 million units in 2010.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2002, cell phones with an integrated camera had been introduced and in 2003 the cell phone with an integrated camera had sold 80 million units per year.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] By 2011, cell phones with an integrated camera were selling hundreds of millions per year, which were causing a decline in digital cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In 2015, digital camera sales were 35 million units or only less than a third of digital camera sales numbers at their peak and also slightly less than film camera sold number at their peak.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] A common alternative is the use of a card reader which may be capable of reading several types of storage media, as well as high speed transfer of data to the computer.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Use of a card reader also avoids draining the camera battery during the download process.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] An external card reader allows convenient direct access to the images on a collection of storage media.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] But if only one storage card is in use, moving it back and forth between the camera and the reader can be inconvenient.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many computers have a card reader built in, at least for SD cards.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many modern cameras support the PictBridge standard, which allows them to send data directly to a PictBridge-capable printer without the need for a computer.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] PictBridge uses PTP to transfer images and control information.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Wireless connectivity can also provide for printing photos without a cable connection.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] An *instant-print camera*, is a digital camera with a built-in printer.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] This confers a similar functionality as an instant camera which uses instant film to quickly generate a physical photograph.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Such non-digital cameras were popularized by Polaroid with the SX-70 in 1972.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras include a video output port.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Usually sVideo, it sends a standard-definition video signal to a television, allowing the user to show one picture at a time.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Buttons or menus on the camera allow the user to select the photo, advance from one to another, or automatically send a "slide show" to the TV.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] HDMI has been adopted by many high-end digital camera makers, to show photos in their high-resolution quality on an HDTV.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] In January 2008, Silicon Image announced a new technology for sending video from mobile devices to a television in digital form.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] MHL sends pictures as a video stream, up to 1080p resolution, and is compatible with HDMI.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some DVD recorders and television sets can read memory cards used in cameras; alternatively several types of flash card readers have TV output capability.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Cameras can be equipped with a varying amount of environmental sealing to provide protection against splashing water, moisture (humidity and fog), dust and sand, or complete waterproofness to a certain depth and for a certain duration.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The latter is one of the approaches to allow underwater photography, the other approach being the use of waterproof housings.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many waterproof digital cameras are also shockproof and resistant to low temperatures.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Some waterproof cameras can be fitted with a waterproof housing to increase the operational depth range.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] The Olympus 'Tough' range of compact cameras is an example.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras have preset modes for different applications.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Within the constraints of correct exposure various parameters can be changed, including exposure, aperture, focusing, light metering, white balance, and equivalent sensitivity.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] For example, a portrait might use a wider aperture to render the background out of focus, and would seek out and focus on a human face rather than other image content.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Few cameras are equipped with a voice note (audio-only) recording feature.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p01] Firmwares may be equipped with the ability to select a suitable scene mode automatically through artificial intelligence.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Many camera phones and most stand alone digital cameras store image data in flash memory cards or other removable media.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Most stand-alone cameras use SD format, while a few use CompactFlash, CFexpress or other types.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] In January 2012, a faster XQD card format was announced.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] In early 2014, some high end cameras have two hot-swappable memory slots.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Photographers can swap one of the memory card with camera-on.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Each memory slot can accept either Compact Flash or SD Card.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] All new Sony cameras also have two memory slots, one for its Memory Stick and one for SD Card, but not hot-swapable.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The approximate count of remaining photos until space exhaustion is calculated by the firmware throughout use and indicated in the viewfinder, to prepare the user for an impending necessary hot swap of the memory card, and/or file offload.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] A few cameras used other removable storage such as Microdrives (very small hard disk drives), CD single (185 MB), and 3.5" floppy disks (e. g.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Most manufacturers of digital cameras do not provide drivers and software to allow their cameras to work with Linux or other free software.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Still, many cameras use the standard USB mass storage and/or Media Transfer Protocol, and are thus widely supported.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Other cameras are supported by the gPhoto project, and many computers are equipped with a memory card reader.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The Joint Photography Experts Group standard (JPEG) is the most common file format for storing image data.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Other file types include Tagged Image File Format (TIFF), High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF), and various Raw image formats.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Many cameras, especially high-end ones, support a raw image format.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] A raw image is the unprocessed set of pixel data directly from the camera's sensor, often saved in a proprietary format.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Adobe Systems has released the DNG format, a royalty-free raw image format used by at least 10 camera manufacturers.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Raw files initially had to be processed in specialized image editing programs, but over time many mainstream editing programs, such as Google's Picasa, have added support for raw images.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Rendering to standard images from raw sensor data allows more flexibility in making major adjustments without losing image quality or retaking the picture.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Formats for movies are AVI, DV, MPEG, MOV (often containing motion JPEG), WMV, and ASF (basically the same as WMV).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Recent formats include MP4, which is based on the QuickTime format and uses newer compression algorithms to allow longer recording times in the same space.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Other formats that are used in cameras (but not for pictures) are the Design Rule for Camera Format (DCF), an ISO specification, used in almost all camera since 1998, which defines an internal file structure and naming.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Also used is the Digital Print Order Format (DPOF), which dictates what order images are to be printed in and how many copies.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The DCF 1998 defines a logical file system with 8.3 filenames and makes the usage of either FAT12, FAT16, FAT32 or exFAT mandatory for its physical layer to maximize platform interoperability.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Most cameras include Exif data that provides metadata about the picture.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Exif data may include aperture, exposure time, focal length, date and time taken.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] To guarantee interoperability, DCF specifies the file system for image and sound files to be used on formatted DCF media (like removable or non-removable memory) as FAT12, FAT16, FAT32, or exFAT.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Media with a capacity of more than 2 GB must be formatted using FAT32 or exFAT.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] These directories contain files with names such as "ABCD1234.JPG" that consist of four alphanumeric characters (often "100_", "DSC0", "DSCF", "IMG_", "MOV_", or "P000"), followed by a number.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Handling of directories with possibly user-created duplicate numbers may vary among camera firmwares.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] DCF 2.0 adds support for DCF optional files recorded in an optional color space (that is, Adobe RGB rather than sRGB).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Such files must be indicated by a leading "_" (as in "_DSC" instead of "100_" or "DSC0").
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] To enable loading many images in miniature view quickly and efficiently, and to retain meta data, some vendors' firmwares generate accompanying low-resolution thumbnail files for videos and raw photos.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] For example, those of Canon cameras end with `.THM`.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] JPEG can already store a thumbnail image standalone.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras have become smaller over time, resulting in an ongoing need to develop a battery small enough to fit in the camera and yet able to power it for a reasonable length of time.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras use either proprietary or standard consumer batteries.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] As of March 2014, most cameras use proprietary lithium-ion batteries while some use standard AA batteries or primarily use a proprietary Lithium-ion rechargeable battery pack but have an optional AA battery holder available.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The most common class of battery used in digital cameras is proprietary battery formats.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] These are built to a manufacturer's custom specifications.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Almost all proprietary batteries are lithium-ion.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] In addition to being available from the OEM, aftermarket replacement batteries are commonly available for most camera models.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras which use off-the-shelf batteries are typically designed to be able to use both single-use disposable and rechargeable batteries, but not with both types in use at the same time.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The most common off-the-shelf battery size used is AA.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] CR2, CR-V3 batteries, and AAA batteries are also used in some cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The CR2 and CR-V3 batteries are lithium based, intended for a single use.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Rechargeable RCR-V3 lithium-ion batteries are also available as an alternative to non-rechargeable CR-V3 batteries.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Some battery grips for DSLRs come with a separate holder to accommodate AA cells as an external power source.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] When digital cameras became common, many photographers asked whether their film cameras could be converted to digital.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The answer was not immediately clear, as it differed among models.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] For the majority of 35 mm film cameras the answer is no, the reworking and cost would be too great, especially as lenses have been evolving as well as cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] For most a conversion to digital, to give enough space for the electronics and allow a liquid crystal display to preview, would require removing the back of the camera and replacing it with a custom built digital unit.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Many early professional SLR cameras, such as the Kodak DCS series, were developed from 35 mm film cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The technology of the time, however, meant that rather than being digital "backs" the bodies of these cameras were mounted on large, bulky digital units, often bigger than the camera portion itself.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] These were factory built cameras, however, not aftermarket conversions.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] A notable exception is the Nikon E2 and Nikon E3, using additional optics to convert the 35 mm format to a 2/3 CCD-sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] A few 35 mm cameras have had digital camera backs made by their manufacturer, Leica being a notable example with the Leica R8–R9.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Medium format and large format cameras (those using film stock greater than 35 mm), have a low unit production, and typical digital backs for them cost over $10,000.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] These cameras also tend to be highly modular, with handgrips, film backs, winders, and lenses available separately to fit various needs.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The very large sensor these backs use leads to enormous image sizes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] For example, Phase One's P45 39 MP image back creates a single TIFF image of size up to 224.6 MB, and even greater pixel counts are available.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Medium format digitals such as this are geared more towards studio and portrait photography than their smaller DSLR counterparts; the ISO speed in particular tends to have a maximum of 400, versus 6400 for some DSLR cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] (Canon EOS-1D Mark IV and Nikon D3S have ISO 12800 plus Hi-3 ISO 102400 with the Canon EOS-1Dx's ISO of 204800).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] In the industrial and high-end professional photography market, some camera systems use modular (removable) image sensors.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] For example, some medium format SLR cameras, such as the Mamiya 645D series, allow installation of either a digital camera back or a traditional photographic film back.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Linear array cameras are also called scan backs.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Most earlier digital camera backs used linear array sensors, moving vertically to digitize the image.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Many of them only capture grayscale images.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The relatively long exposure times, in the range of seconds or even minutes generally limit scan backs to studio applications, where all aspects of the photographic scene are under the photographer's control.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Some other camera backs use CCD arrays similar to typical cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Since it is much easier to manufacture a high-quality linear CCD array with only thousands of pixels than a CCD matrix with millions, very high resolution linear CCD camera backs were available much earlier than their CCD matrix counterparts.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] For example, you could buy an (albeit expensive) camera back with over 7,000 pixel horizontal resolution in the mid-1990s.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] However, as of 2004, it is still difficult to buy a comparable CCD matrix camera of the same resolution.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Rotating line cameras, with about 10,000 color pixels in its sensor line, are able, as of 2005, to capture about 120,000 lines during one full 360-degree rotation, thereby creating a single digital image of 1,200 Megapixels.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] Most modern digital camera backs use CCD or CMOS matrix sensors.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] The matrix sensor captures the entire image frame at once, instead of incrementing scanning the frame area through the prolonged exposure.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] For example, Phase One produces a 39 million pixel digital camera back with a 49.1 × 36.8 mm CCD in 2008.
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] This CCD array is a little smaller than a frame of 120 film and much larger than a 35 mm frame (36 × 24 mm).
[src:rewindpix/digital-camera-p02] In comparison, consumer digital cameras use arrays ranging from 36 × 24 mm (full frame on high end consumer DSLRs) to 1.28 × 0.96 mm (on camera phones) CMOS sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] A **digital detox** is a deliberate break from digital devices to mitigate screen overuse and promote offline activities.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Emerging in response to increasing technology use, the practice addresses concerns about screen addiction's impact on health and mental well-being.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Detox approaches range from setting limits on device usage to complete abstinence, sometimes supported by dedicated retreats or travel packages.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Though digital detoxes have shown positive effects on focus, relationships, and overall well-being, they may also raise social pressures and fear of missing out (FOMO).
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] A **digital detox** is a period of time when a person voluntarily refrains from using digital devices such as smartphones, computers, and social media platforms.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] It encourages awareness of technology use and is aimed at mitigating digital dependency and promoting offline engagement.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Subsets of a digital detox include varying levels of decreased electronic use, messaging, social media, and applications.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Since 2015, discussion and research on the implications of a digital detox have increased.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] The areas of research can be broken into five main categories: communication, education, tourism, well-being and health, and work environments.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] The increase in technological advancements has led to a growing demand for research on digital detoxes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] The use of video conferencing during COVID-19 has increased the stress-related depletion of physiological resources, leading to negative effects on health.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Celebrities and influencers have promoted the concept of a digital detox.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Ed Sheeran and Kendall Jenner have undergone a social media detox and influenced others to do one as well.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Comedian Ari Shaffir gained attention for refusing to use a smartphone after concerns about spending too much time on it, especially on social media.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] A digital detox aims to counteract the negative impacts of excessive screen and technology use, which can lead to both physical and mental health issues.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Physical effects of technology addiction include illness caused by germs on a phone, eye strain, wrist strain, and neck problems.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Neck problems, sometimes called "tech neck", may arise due to leaning the head forward for extended periods to look at a phone.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] This can lead to chronic pain and deformities such as hunchback.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Neck and back pain from excessive phone use can also lead to extreme migraines.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Screen time also has an impact on the brain, especially grey matter and the cerebral cortex.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Adults with a diagnosed smartphone addiction have lower gray matter volume and a thinner cerebral cortex compared to those of adults without smartphone addictions.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Gray matter is responsible for movement, memory, and emotions.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] The cerebral cortex is responsible for memory, decision-making, and problem-solving.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Sleep habits are also impacted by smartphone use, as blue light from screens can disrupt sleep patterns through the suppression of the hormone melatonin.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] This hormone imbalance from diminished melatonin disrupts the REM sleep cycle which is essential for storing memories in the brain.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Technology reprograms people to feel more anxious when they are not in its presence.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Additionally, having a phone close to a person's face can trigger a fight or flight response, setting an anxious tone for the day.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Screen time's effect on mental health can also be demonstrated through a positive correlation between depression and screen time.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Screen time, specifically in the form of social media, has been found to harm self-esteem.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Screen addiction shares some characteristics with other addictions including alcohol dependence and gambling.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Reward-style games, such as some downloadable on smartphones, have been found to lead to obsessive behaviors.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Additionally, screen addiction can affect children's ability to learn and focus.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] The process of a digital detox can vary widely depending on an individual's goals, motivations, and lifestyle.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Methods include deleting media platforms, muting notifications, and abstaining entirely from digital media.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] There are three different variables in a digital detox: time frame, the extent of intervention, and the amount of outside assistance.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Generally, digital detoxification can be split into two categories: moderate and complete.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] A moderate digital detox involves limiting device and social media usage.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Common executions in a moderate detox center on setting boundaries.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Examples of boundaries include limiting social media usage to specific times of day or implementing screen-free periods, especially in the morning or evening.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] One way of curbing the overuse of digital devices is to allocate some of the uses of a smartphone to non-digital means.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] In 2019 Google announced a "paper phone" which can contain daily agendas, directions, and other uses so that people rely less on their smartphones.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Another key element of a moderate detox is controlling the frequency of notifications and alerts.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] This can alleviate the temptation to check devices continuously throughout the day.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] A complete detox is an absolute break from digital devices for a set period.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] This form of detox can be conducted for various periods, the most common ranging between a week and a month.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] During a complete detox, individuals delete or log out of all social media and messaging apps.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Some individuals implement this form of detox during a vacation or a period when there are no work or social obligations that would require their online presence.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] The tourism industry has found a niche market for "digital detox travel packages" where tourists are disconnected from their information and communications technology by traveling to remote areas.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] A study from University of Nottingham Ningbo China found that the biggest motivators for embarking on a digital detox holiday include mindfulness, technostress, relaxation, and self-expression.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Digital detox retreats increase accountability among individuals and prevent the temptation to check devices or engage in habitual online activities.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Digital detoxes have been found to have a positive impact on relationships from a refocus on offline social interactions.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] People can build stronger social bonds when they do not check their phones as frequently.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Despite this positive impact, studies have found negative effects of digital detoxes on social relationships and interactions.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Digital detoxes have also been shown to cause a higher social pressure on participants during social media abstinence compared to pre-intervention social pressure measurements.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Furthermore, some research indicates that digital detoxes can result in the fear of missing out (FOMO) on social activities.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Digital detoxes have been found to have positive effects on physical health, such as reducing eye strain, dry eyes, and blurry vision.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Additionally, a digital detox can address neck pain caused by being in a hunched position from looking at a phone.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Furthermore, detoxing has been shown to improve time perception in participants.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] One 2023 meta-analysis found that subjective and psychological well-being increased with reduced daily social media use, though it cautioned that the observed effect sizes were small.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] It also observed that digital detoxing interventions did reduce depression levels.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] In February 2025, the results of a month-long randomized controlled trial were published in PNAS Nexus which investigated the causal effects of restricting mobile internet access on psychological functioning.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] The researchers found that restricting such access led to significant improvements in mental health, subjective well-being, and objective measurements of attention span.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] They concluded that constant connectivity may be detrimental to cognitive performance and emotional health.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] In contrast, a 2025 meta-analysis noted that temporary social media abstinence did not significantly affect positive affect, negative affect, or life satisfaction.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Another 2025 meta-analysis found that temporary social media abstinence improved subjective well-being, but noted that the observed effect sizes were small.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] A subset of digital detox is social media detox, which is a period of time when individuals voluntarily stay away from social media.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] In academic research, social media detoxification is commonly referred to as the "non-use of social media", and falls under the umbrella of *digital detox*, with a focus specifically on unplugging from social media.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that 69% of adults in the United States used Facebook, 73% used YouTube, and 37% used Instagram.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] A 2012 study found that around 60% of Facebook users have made a conscious effort to voluntarily take a break from Facebook for a time period of several weeks or more.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] This has been referred to as "media refusal", with non-users known as "social media rejectors" who once used social media but have now voluntarily given it up for various reasons.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] In the 2010s, technology and social media became an integral aspect of everyday life, and thus the decision to refrain from using technology or social media has become a conscious lifestyle choice reflecting the desire for selective and reversible disconnection.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Undoubtedly, in the digital age, social media plays a vital role in building social capital, maintaining connections, and managing impressions.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Scholars have argued for the importance of maintaining a certain level of distraction that social media can provide for a balanced state of body and mind, and some scholars have even debated that social media is necessary and should not be completely cut out.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] That being said, many scholars believe that the moderation of social media is essential, primarily due to social media platforms' goal of encouraging constant use with likes, notifications, and infinite scrolling.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Furthermore, to lessen the effects of these addictive features social media platforms such as Instagram have begun to explore alternative methods, such as making likes on a user's post invisible to the user, to shift the focus away from constant notifications and likes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Some companies have even launched movements against technology addiction.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] For example, in October 2019, Google and Special Projects (an award-winning design and invention studio based in London) released Paper Phone, a Google product consisting of a printed piece of paper folded into eighths that contains relevant information to your day much like a daily planner.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] The motive behind the project was to provide the utility of a smartphone in a simplistic and less dynamic delivery.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Moreover, other projects have focused on building second phones with less functionality, or putting human nature and design above technology.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Some critics disagree with Google's approach to the digital detox phenomenon, however, and instead argue that harmony between technology use and well-being can be achieved.
[src:rewindpix/digital-detox] Additionally, these critics suggest that the best way to digitally detox is to be mindful of the amount of time that is being spent on a digital device.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] A **digital single-lens reflex camera** (**digital SLR** or **DSLR**) is a digital camera that combines the optics and mechanisms of a single-lens reflex camera with a solid-state image sensor and digitally records the images from the sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The reflex design scheme is the primary difference between a DSLR and other digital cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In the reflex design, light travels through the lens and then to a mirror that alternates to send the image to either a prism, which shows the image in the optical viewfinder, or the image sensor when the shutter release button is pressed.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The viewfinder of a DSLR presents an image that will not differ substantially from what is captured by the camera's sensor, as it presents it as a direct optical view through the main camera lens rather than showing an image through a separate secondary lens.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] DSLRs largely replaced film-based SLRs during the 2000s.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Major camera manufacturers began to transition their product lines away from DSLR cameras to mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras beginning in the 2010s.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Smith invented charge-coupled semiconductor devices, which can be used as analog storage registers and image sensors.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] A CCD (Charge-Coupled Device) imager provides a low-noise analog image signal, which is digitized when used in a digital camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] For their contribution to digital photography, Boyle and Smith were awarded the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 1973, Fairchild developed a 100 x 100 pixel interline CCD image sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] This CCD was used in the first commercial CCD camera, the Fairchild MV-100, which was introduced in late 1973.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 1974, Kodak scientists Peter Dillon and Albert Brault used this Fairchild CCD 202 image sensor to create the first color CCD image sensor by fabricating a red, green, and blue color filter array that was registered and bonded to the CCD.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 1975, Kodak engineer Steven Sasson built the first portable, battery-operated digital still camera, which used a zoom lens from a Kodak Super 8mm movie camera and a monochrome Fairchild 100×100 pixel CCD.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The first prototype filmless SLR camera was publicly demonstrated by Sony in August 1981.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The Sony Mavica (a magnetic still video camera) used a color-striped 2/3” format CCD sensor with 280K pixels, along with analog video signal processing and recording.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The Mavica electronic still camera employed a TTL single-lens reflex viewfinder, as shown in the graphic from a June 1982 Sony press release.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] It recorded FM-modulated analog video signals on a newly developed 2” magnetic floppy disk, dubbed the "Mavipak".
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The disk format was later standardized as the "Still Video Floppy", or "SVF", so the Sony Mavica was the first "SVF-SLR" to be demonstrated, but it was not a D-SLR since it recorded analog video images rather than digital images.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Starting in 1983, many Japanese companies demonstrated prototype SVF cameras, including Toshiba, Canon, Copal, Hitachi, Panasonic, Sanyo, and Mitsubishi.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The Canon RC-701, introduced in May 1986, was the first SVF camera (and the first SVF-SLR camera) sold in the US.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] It employed an SLR viewfinder and included a 2/3” format color CCD sensor with 380K pixels.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] It was sold along with removable 11-66mm and 50-150mm zoom lens.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Over the next five years, many other companies began selling SVF analog electronic cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] These included the monochrome Nikon QV-1000C SVF-SLR camera, introduced in 1988, which had a specialized QV-mount (a non-F-mount) for interchangeable QV Nikkor lenses.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 1986, the Kodak Microelectronics Technology Division developed a 1.3 MP CCD image sensor, the first with more than 1 million pixels.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 1987, this sensor was integrated with a Canon F-1 film SLR body at the Kodak Federal Systems Division to create an early DSLR camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The digital back monitored the camera body battery current to sync the image sensor exposure to the film body shutter.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Digital images were stored on a tethered hard drive and processed for histogram feedback to the user.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] This camera was created for the U.S. government, and was followed by several other models intended for government use and eventually Kodak DCS, a commercial DSLR series launched in 1991.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 1995, Nikon co-developed the Nikon E series with Fujifilm.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The E series included the Nikon E2/E2S, Nikon E2N/E2NS and Nikon E3/E3S, with the E3S released in December 1999.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In the late 1990s, Sony introduced the "Digital Mavica" series of consumer digital cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Unlike the original analog Mavica, the Digital Mavica cameras recorded JPEG compressed image files on standard 3½-inch magnetic floppy discettes (meant to simplify camera-to-computer data transfer) and did not have an SLR viewfinder.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The D1's body was similar to Nikon's professional 35 mm film SLRs, and it had the same Nikkor lens mount, allowing the D1 to use Nikon's existing line of AI/AIS manual focus and AF lenses.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Although Nikon and other manufacturers had produced digital SLR cameras for several years prior, the D1 was the first professional digital SLR that displaced Kodak's then-undisputed reign over the professional market.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Over the next decade, other camera manufacturers entered the DSLR market, including Canon, Kodak, Fujifilm, Minolta (later Konica Minolta, and ultimately acquired by Sony), Pentax (whose camera division is now owned by Ricoh), Olympus, Panasonic, Samsung, Sigma, and Sony.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In January 2000, Fujifilm announced the FinePix S1 Pro, the first consumer-level DSLR.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In November 2001, Canon released its 4.1-megapixel EOS-1D, the brand's first professional digital body.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 2003, Canon introduced the 6.3-megapixel EOS 300D SLR camera (known in the United States and Canada as the Digital Rebel and in Japan as the Kiss Digital) with an MSRP of US$999, aimed at the consumer market.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Its commercial success encouraged other manufacturers to produce competing digital SLRs, lowering entry costs and allowing more amateur photographers to purchase DSLRs.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 2004, Konica Minolta released the Konica Minolta Maxxum 7D, the first DSLR with in-body image stabilization which later become standard in Pentax, Olympus, and Sony Alpha cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In early 2008, Nikon released the D90, the first DSLR to feature video recording.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Since then, all major companies have offered cameras with this functionality.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Over time, the number of megapixels in imaging sensors has increased steadily, with most companies focusing on high ISO performance, speed of focus, higher frame rates, the elimination of digital 'noise' produced by the imaging sensor, and price reductions to lure new customers.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In June 2012, Canon announced the first DSLR to feature a touchscreen, the EOS 650D/Rebel T4i/Kiss X6i.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Although this feature had been widely used on both compact cameras and mirrorless models, it had not made an appearance on a DSLR until the 650D.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The DSLR market is dominated by Japanese companies, and the top five manufacturers are Japanese: Canon, Nikon, Olympus, Pentax, and Sony.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Other manufacturers of DSLRs include Mamiya, Sigma, Leica (Germany), and Hasselblad (Swedish).
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 2007, Canon edged out Nikon with 41% of worldwide sales to the latter's 40%, followed by Sony and Olympus, each with approximately 6% market share.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In the Japanese domestic market, Nikon captured 43.3% to Canon's 39.9%, with Pentax a distant third at 6.3%.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 2008, Canon's and Nikon's offerings took the majority of sales.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 2010, Canon controlled 44.5% of the DSLR market, followed by Nikon with 29.8% and Sony with 11.9%.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] For Canon and Nikon, digital SLRs were their biggest source of profit in the early 2010s.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Canon's DSLRs brought in four times the profits of their compact digital cameras, while Nikon earned more from DSLRs and lenses than from any other product.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Olympus and Panasonic have since exited the DSLR market and now focus on producing mirrorless cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 2013, after a decade of double-digit growth, DSLR (along with MILC) sales were down 15 per cent.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] This may be due to some low-end DSLR users choosing to use a smartphone instead.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The market intelligence firm IDC predicted that Nikon would be out of business by 2018 if the trend continued, although this did not come to pass.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Regardless, the market has shifted from being driven by hardware to software, and camera manufacturers have not been keeping up.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Beginning in the 2010s, major camera manufacturers began to transition their product lines away from DSLR cameras to mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras (MILCs).
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In September 2013, Olympus announced they would stop the development of DSLR cameras and focus on the development of MILCs.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Nikon announced they were ending production of DSLRs in Japan in 2020, followed by similar announcements from Canon and Sony.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 2021, mirrorless cameras began to outsell DSLRs for the first time since their introduction; this trend has continued as all major camera brands other than Pentax have ceased production of new consumer DSLR models as of 2025.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Contax, Fujifilm, Kodak, Panasonic, Olympus, Sigma, Sony, and Samsung all previously produced DSLRs but now either exclusively offer non-DSLR systems or have left the camera market entirely.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Currently, DSLRs are widely used by consumers and professional still photographers.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Well-established DSLRs currently offer a wide variety of dedicated lenses and other equipment and can be found for lower prices than newer mirrorless cameras; however, the majority of companies that historically produced DSLRs have since ceased production in favor of mirrorless systems.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Mainstream DSLRs (in full-frame or smaller image sensor format) are produced by Nikon and Pentax.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Phase One, Hasselblad, and Mamiya Leaf produce expensive, high-end medium-format DSLRs, including some with removable sensor backs.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Konica Minolta's line of DSLRs was purchased by Sony.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Like SLRs, DSLRs typically use interchangeable lenses with a proprietary lens mount.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] A movable mechanical mirror system is switched down (to precisely a 45-degree angle) to direct light from the lens over a matte focusing screen via a condenser lens and a pentaprism/pentamirror to an optical viewfinder eyepiece.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Most entry-level DSLRs use a pentamirror instead of the traditional pentaprism.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Focusing can be manual, by twisting the focus on the lens; or automatic, activated by pressing half-way on the shutter release or a dedicated auto-focus (AF) button.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] To take an image, the mirror swings upwards in the direction of the arrow, the focal-plane shutter opens, and the image is projected and captured on the image sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] After these actions, the shutter closes, the mirror returns to the 45-degree angle, and the built-in drive mechanism re-tensions the shutter for the next exposure.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Compared with the newer concept of mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras, this mirror/prism system is the characteristic difference, providing direct, accurate optical preview with separate autofocus and exposure metering sensors.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Essential parts of all digital cameras are some electronics like amplifiers, analog-to-digital converters, image processors, and other microprocessors for processing the digital image, performing data storage, and/or driving an electronic display.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] DSLRs typically use autofocus based on phase detection.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] This method allows the optimal lens position to be calculated rather than "found", as would be the case with autofocus based on contrast maximization.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Phase-detection autofocus is typically faster than other passive techniques.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] As the phase sensor requires the same light going to the image sensor, it was previously only possible with an SLR design.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] However, with the introduction of focal-plane phase-detect autofocusing in mirrorless interchangeable lens cameras by Sony, Fuji, Olympus, and Panasonic, cameras can now employ both phase detect and contrast-detect AF points.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Digital SLR cameras, along with most other digital cameras, generally have a mode dial to access standard camera settings or automatic scene-mode settings.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Sometimes called a "PASM" dial, they typically provide modes such as program, aperture-priority, shutter-priority, and full manual modes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Scene modes vary from camera to camera, and these modes are inherently less customizable.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] They often include landscape, portrait, action, macro, night, and silhouette, among others.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] However, these different settings and shooting styles that "scene" mode provides can be achieved by calibrating certain settings on the camera.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] A method to prevent dust from entering the chamber by using a "dust cover" filter right behind the lens mount was used by Sigma in its first DSLR, the Sigma SD9, in 2002.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Olympus used a built-in sensor cleaning mechanism in its first DSLR that had a sensor exposed to air, the Olympus E-1, in 2003 (all previous models each had a non-interchangeable lens, preventing direct exposure of the sensor to outside environmental conditions).
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Several Canon DSLR cameras rely on dust reduction systems based on vibrating the sensor at ultrasonic frequencies to remove dust from the sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Interchangeable lenses for SLRs and DSLRs are built to operate correctly with a specific lens mount that is generally unique to each brand.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] A photographer will often use lenses made by the same manufacturer as the camera body (for example, Canon EF lenses on a Canon body) although there are also many independent lens manufacturers, such as Sigma, Tamron, Tokina, and Vivitar, that make lenses for a variety of different lens mounts.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] There are also lens adapters that allow a lens for one lens mount to be used on a camera body with a different lens mount, but with often reduced functionality.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Many lenses are mountable, "diaphragm-and-meter-compatible", on modern DSLRs, and on older film SLRs that use the same lens mount.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] However, when lenses designed for 35 mm film or equivalently sized digital image sensors are used on DSLRs with smaller sized sensors, the image is effectively cropped and the lens appears to have a longer focal length than its stated focal length.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Most DSLR manufacturers have introduced lines of lenses with image circles optimised for the smaller sensors and focal lengths equivalent to those generally offered for existing 35 mm mount DSLRs, mostly in the wide-angle range.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] These lenses tend not to be completely compatible with full-frame sensors or 35 mm film because of the smaller imaging circle and with some Canon EF-S lenses, interfere with the reflex mirrors on full-frame bodies.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Since 2008, manufacturers have offered DSLRs which offer a movie mode capable of recording high definition motion video.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] A DSLR with this feature is often known as an HDSLR or DSLR video shooter.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The first DSLR introduced with an HD movie mode, the Nikon D90, captures video at 720p24 (1280x720 resolution at 24 frame/s).
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Other early HDSLRs capture video using a nonstandard video resolution or frame rate.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] For example, the Pentax K-7 uses a nonstandard resolution of 1536×1024, which matches the imager's 3:2 aspect ratio.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The Canon EOS 500D (Rebel T1i) uses a nonstandard frame rate of 20 frame/s at 1080p, along with a more conventional 720p30 format.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In general, HDSLRs use the full imager area to capture HD video, though not all pixels (causing video artifacts to some degree).
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Compared with the much smaller image sensors found in the typical camcorder, the HDSLR's much larger sensor yields distinctly different image characteristics.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] HDSLRs can achieve much shallower depth of field and superior low-light performance.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] However, the low ratio of active pixels (to total pixels) is more susceptible to aliasing artifacts (such as moiré patterns) in scenes with particular textures, and CMOS rolling shutter tends to be more severe.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Furthermore, due to the DSLR's optical construction, HDSLRs typically lack one or more video functions found on standard dedicated camcorders, such as autofocus while shooting, powered zoom, and an electronic viewfinder/preview.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] These and other handling limitations prevent the HDSLR from being operated as a simple point-and-shoot camcorder, instead of demanding some level of planning and skill for location shooting.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The Canon EOS 5D Mark II (with the release of firmware version 2.0.3/2.0.4.) and Panasonic Lumix GH1 were the first HDSLRs to offer 1080p video at 24fps, and since then the list of models with comparable functionality has grown considerably.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The rapid maturation of HDSLR cameras has sparked a revolution in digital filmmaking (referred to as "DSLR revolution"), and the "Shot On DSLR" badge is a quickly growing phrase among independent filmmakers.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Canon's North American TV advertisements featuring the Rebel T1i have been shot using the T1i itself.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Other types of HDSLRs found their distinct application in the field of documentary and ethnographic filmmaking, especially due to their affordability, technical and aesthetical features, and their ability to make observation highly intimate.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] An increased number of films, television shows, and other productions are utilizing the quickly improving features.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] One such project was Canon's "Story Beyond the Still" contest that asked filmmakers to collectively shoot a short film in 8 chapters, with each chapter being shot over a short period of time and a winner was determined for each chapter.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] After 7 chapters the winners collaborated to shoot the final chapter of the story.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Due to the affordability and convenient size of HDSLRs compared with professional movie cameras, The Avengers used five Canon EOS 5D Mark II and two Canon 7D to shoot the scenes from various vantage angles throughout the set and reduced the number of reshoots of complex action scenes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Manufacturers have sold optional accessories to optimize a DSLR camera as a video camera, such as a shotgun-type microphone, and an External EVF with 1.2 million pixels.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Early DSLRs lacked the ability to show the optical viewfinder's image on the LCD screen – a feature known as live preview.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Live preview is useful in situations where the camera's eye-level viewfinder cannot be used, such as underwater photography where the camera is enclosed in a plastic waterproof case.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 2000, Olympus introduced the Olympus E-10, the first DSLR with live preview – albeit with an atypical fixed lens design.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In late 2008, some DSLRs from Canon, Nikon, Olympus, Panasonic, Leica, Pentax, Samsung and Sony all provided continuous live preview as an option.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Additionally, the Fujifilm FinePix S5 Pro offers 30 seconds of live preview.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] On almost all DSLRs that offer live preview via the primary sensor, the phase-detection autofocus system does not work in the live preview mode, and the DSLR switches to a slower contrast system commonly found in point-and-shoot cameras.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] While even phase detection autofocus requires contrast in the scene, strict contrast-detection autofocus is limited in its ability to find focus quickly, though it is somewhat more accurate.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] In 2012, Canon introduced hybrid autofocus technology to the DSLR in the EOS 650D/Rebel T4i, and introduced a more sophisticated version, which it calls "Dual Pixel CMOS AF", with the EOS 70D.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The technology allows certain pixels to act as both contrast-detection and phase-detection pixels, thereby greatly improving autofocus speed in live view (although it remains slower than pure phase detection).
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] While several mirrorless cameras, plus Sony's fixed-mirror SLTs, have similar hybrid AF systems, Canon is the only manufacturer that offers such technology in DSLRs.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] A new feature via a separate software package introduced from Breeze Systems in October 2007, features live view from a distance.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The software package is named "DSLR Remote Pro v1.5" and enables support for the Canon EOS 40D and 1D Mark III.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Image sensors used in DSLRs come in a range of sizes.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The very largest are the ones used in "medium format" cameras, typically via a "digital back" which can be used as an alternative to a film back.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Because of the manufacturing costs of these large sensors, the price of these cameras is typically over $1,500 and easily reaching $8,000 and beyond as of February 2021.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] "Full-frame" is the same size as 35 mm film (135 film, image format 24×36 mm); these sensors are used in DSLRs such as the Canon EOS-1D X Mark II, 5DS/5DSR, 5D Mark IV and 6D Mark II, and the Nikon D5, D850, D750, D610 and Df.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Most lower-cost DSLRs use a smaller sensor that is APS-C sized, which is approximately 24×16 mm, slightly smaller than the size of an APS-C film frame, or about 40% of the area of a full-frame sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Leica offers an "S-System" DSLR with a 30×45 mm array containing 37 million pixels.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] This sensor is 56% larger than a full-frame sensor.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The resolution of DSLR sensors is typically measured in megapixels.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] More expensive cameras and cameras with larger sensors tend to have higher megapixel ratings.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] A larger megapixel rating does not mean higher quality.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Low light sensitivity is a good example of this.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] When comparing two sensors of the same size, for example, two APS-C sensors one 12.1 MP and one 18 MP, the one with the lower megapixel rating will usually perform better in low light.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] This is because the size of the individual pixels is larger, and more light is landing on each pixel, compared with the sensor with more megapixels.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] This is not always the case, because newer cameras that have higher megapixels also have better noise reduction software, and higher ISO settings to make up for the loss of light per pixel due to higher pixel density.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The lenses typically used on DSLRs have a wider range of apertures available to them, ranging from as large as f/0.9 to about f/32.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] Lenses for smaller sensor cameras rarely have true available aperture sizes much larger than f/2.8 or much smaller than f/5.6.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] To help extend the exposure range, some smaller sensor cameras will also incorporate an ND filter pack into the aperture mechanism.
[src:rewindpix/digital-single-lens-reflex-camera] The apertures that smaller sensor cameras have available give much more depth of field than equivalent angles of view on a DSLR.
